commit_message:
Create an admin domain and cloud_admin user

Move towards a full keystone v3 setup. We create the admin domain and
create a user that is capable of managing domains. To do this we need to
create the users, modify the config and restart the keystone service
with the new policy information.

Change-Id: I43160a888503bd6b2112a874b134b93d9962e53c

commit_message:
Fix enabled/dependency relationship in project dashboard

This patch addresses the problem that the fixed
dependencies in the hz.dashboard module are dependent on
javascript being loaded from an "enabled" file that might
be disabled, thus breaking the module, and the application.

Change-Id: I3d89c5e652e152f030f5e2e0ffeaebb071ad4e5e
Closes-Bug: 1466713

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-24 07:58:05.000000000', 'message': 'Add volume drivers for Infortrend Storage

Infortrend implement ISCSI and FC volume drivers for EonStor DS product (DS1000, DS3000)
It manages storage by Infortrend CLI tool.

common_cli.py implements the basic Cinder Driver API.
infortrend_fc_cli.py and infortrend_iscsi_cli.py use them to provide FC and iSCSI specific support.

Support features:
- Volume Create/Delete
- Volume Attach/Detach
- Snapshot Create/Delete
- Create Volume from Snapshot
- Get Volume Stats
- Copy Image to Volume
- Copy Volume to Image
- Clone Volume
- Extend Volume

Change-Id: I830c5a48a5fb85707f02396b4634825e27455e8a
Implements: blueprint infortrend-iscsi-fc-volume-driver

commit_message:
Add volume drivers for Infortrend Storage

Infortrend implement ISCSI and FC volume drivers for
EonStor DS product.
It manages storage by Infortrend CLI tool.

common_cli.py implements the basic Cinder Driver API.
infortrend_fc_cli.py and infortrend_iscsi_cli.py use them to
provide FC and iSCSI specific support.

Support features:
- Volume Create/Delete
- Volume Attach/Detach
- Snapshot Create/Delete
- Create Volume from Snapshot
- Get Volume Stats
- Copy Image to Volume
- Copy Volume to Image
- Clone Volume
- Extend Volume

Change-Id: I830c5a48a5fb85707f02396b4634825e27455e8a
Implements: blueprint infortrend-iscsi-fc-volume-driver

commit_message:
Fix external links

Run "sphinx -b linkcheck" on the RST directories and fix problems found.
In most cases, it's a redirect from http to https.

Change-Id: Ib56ea42f5fd14de3fa79e0559b8086fed6173a0a

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-19 05:20:25.000000000', 'message': 'Allow one object-server per disk deployment

Enabled by a new config boolean, "server_per_port" in the
[DEFAULT] config section for object-server and/or replication server
configs.  In this mode, the parent swift-object-server process
continues to run as the original user (i.e. root if low-port binding
is required), and forks off one worker per unique port defined in all
the rings for the server.  The child, per-port servers will drop
privileges after binding to their specified port.  The parent process
detects dead servers and restarts them (on the correct port), starts
missing servers when an updated ring file is found with a device on
the server with a new port, and kills extraneous servers when their
port is found to no longer be in the ring.  The ring files are
stat'ed at most every "ring_check_interval" seconds, as configured
in the object-server config (same default of 15s).

Immediately stopping all swift-object-worker processes still works by
sending the parent a SIGTERM.  Likewise, a SIGHUP to the parent process
will be propagated to the children who will finish their current
request(s) and then exit.  The drop_privileges helper function now has
an optional param to suppress the setsid() call, which otherwise screws
up the child workers' process management.

The new class method RingData.load_devices() will load only the device
array from a serialized, gzipped ring file, retaining a reference to only
the returned array of device dicts.  This is used to keep the parent and
all forked off workers from unnecessarily having full copies of all
storage policy rings in memory.

A new helper method,
swift.common.storage_policy.all_bind_ports_for_node(), returns a set of
all device ports in all rings for a server (identified by its set of IP
addresses).  The function includes support for caching mtimes of the
ring files, so they are not opened more frequently than necessary (if
no rings have changed mtimes, then None is returned).  This is obviously
used by swift-object-server when server_per_port=True and takes
advantage of RingData.load_devices().

This patch includes enhancements to the probe tests and
object-replicator/object-reconstructor config plumbing to allow the
probe tests to work correctly both in the "normal" config (same IP but
unique ports for each SAIO "server") and a server-per-port setup (unique
127.0.0.x IP for each SAIO "server" and unique port per disk within each
"server", though that's really only noticeable in the EC probe test ring
which has 8 devices, 2 per "server").  Specifically,
swift.common.ring.utils.is_local_device() will ignore the ports when the
"my_port" argument is None.  Then, object-replicator and
object-reconstructor both set self.bind_port to None if server_per_port
is enabled.  Bonus improvement for IPv6 addresses in is_local_device().

This PR for vagrant-swift-all-in-one will aid in testing this patch:
https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/pull/16/

Change-Id: I2239a4000b41a7e7cc53465ce794af49d44796c6

detects dead servers and restarts them (on the correct port), starts
missing servers when an updated ring file is found with a device on
the server with a new port, and kills extraneous servers when their
port is found to no longer be in the ring.  The ring files are
stat'ed at most every "ring_check_interval" seconds, as configured
in the object-server config (same default of 15s).

Immediately stopping all swift-object-worker processes still works by
sending the parent a SIGTERM.  Likewise, a SIGHUP to the parent process
will be propagated to the children who will finish their current
request(s) and then exit.  The drop_privileges helper function now has
an optional param to suppress the setsid() call, which otherwise screws
up the child workers' process management.

The new class method RingData.load_devices() will load only the device
array from a serialized, gzipped ring file, retaining a reference to only
the returned array of device dicts.  This is used to keep the parent and
all forked off workers from unnecessarily having full copies of all
storage policy rings in memory.

A new helper method,
swift.common.storage_policy.all_bind_ports_for_node(), returns a set of
all device ports in all rings for a server (identified by its set of IP
addresses).  The function includes support for caching mtimes of the
ring files, so they are not opened more frequently than necessary (if
no rings have changed mtimes, then None is returned).  This is obviously
used by swift-object-server when server_per_port=True and takes
advantage of RingData.load_devices().

This patch includes enhancements to the probe tests and
object-replicator/object-reconstructor config plumbing to allow the
probe tests to work correctly both in the "normal" config (same IP but
unique ports for each SAIO "server") and a server-per-port setup (unique
127.0.0.x IP for each SAIO "server" and unique port per disk within each
"server", though that's really only noticeable in the EC probe test ring
which has 8 devices, 2 per "server").  Specifically,
swift.common.ring.utils.is_local_device() will ignore the ports when the
"my_port" argument is None.  Then, object-replicator and
object-reconstructor both set self.bind_port to None if server_per_port
is enabled.  Bonus improvement for IPv6 addresses in is_local_device().

This PR for vagrant-swift-all-in-one will aid in testing this patch:
https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/pull/16/

https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/pull/16/

Also allow SAIO to answer is_local_device() better

Common SAIO setups have multiple "servers" all on the same host with
different ports for the different "servers" (which happen to match the
IPs specified in the rings for the devices on each of those "servers").

This breaks down if you want to set up the SAIO to have one
object-server per disk.

However, you can configure the SAIO to have different localhost IP
addresses (e.g. 127.0.0.1, 127.0.0.2, etc.) in the ring and in the
servers' config files' bind_ip setting.

This new whataremyips() implementation combined with a little plumbing
allows is_local_device() to accurately answer, even on an SAIO.

In the default case (an unspecified bind_ip defaults to '0.0.0.0') as
well as an explict "bind to everything" like '0.0.0.0' or '::',
whataremyips() behaves as it always has, returning all IP addresses for
the server.

Also updated probe tests to handle each "server" in the SAIO having a
unique IP address.

DocImpact

'}, {'created': '2015-05-30 23:02:13.000000000', 'message': 'Allow 1+ object-servers-per-disk deployment

Enabled by a new > 0 integer config value, "servers_per_port" in the
[DEFAULT] config section for object-server and/or replication server
configs.  The setting's integer value determines how many different
object-server workers handle requests for any single unique local port
in the ring.  In this mode, the parent swift-object-server process
continues to run as the original user (i.e. root if low-port binding
is required), binds to all ports as defined in the ring, and forks off
the specified number of workers per listen socket.  The child, per-port
servers drop privileges and behave pretty much how object-server workers
always have, except that because the ring has unique ports per disk, the
object-servers will only be handling requests for a single disk.  The
parent process detects dead servers and restarts them (with the correct
listen socket), starts missing servers when an updated ring file is
found with a device on the server with a new port, and kills extraneous
servers when their port is found to no longer be in the ring.  The ring
files are stat'ed at most every "ring_check_interval" seconds, as
configured in the object-server config (same default of 15s).

Immediately stopping all swift-object-worker processes still works by
sending the parent a SIGTERM.  Likewise, a SIGHUP to the parent process
still causes the parent process to close all listen sockets and exit,
allowing existing children to finish serving their existing requests.
The drop_privileges helper function now has an optional param to
suppress the setsid() call, which otherwise screws up the child workers'
process management.

The new class method RingData.load_devices() will load only the device
array from a serialized, gzipped ring file, retaining a reference to only
the returned array of device dicts.  This is used to keep the parent and
all forked off workers from unnecessarily having full copies of all
storage policy rings in memory.

A new helper method,
swift.common.storage_policy.all_bind_ports_for_node(), returns a set of
all device ports in all rings for a server (identified by its set of IP
addresses).  The function includes support for caching mtimes of the
ring files, so they are not opened more frequently than necessary (if
no rings have changed mtimes, then None is returned).  This is used by
swift-object-server when servers_per_port > 0 and takes advantage of
RingData.load_devices().

This patch includes enhancements to the probe tests and
object-replicator/object-reconstructor config plumbing to allow the
probe tests to work correctly both in the "normal" config (same IP but
unique ports for each SAIO "server") and a server-per-port setup where
each SAIO "server" must have a unique IP address and unique port per
disk within each "server".  The main probe tests only work with 4
servers and 4 disks, but you can see the difference in the rings for the
EC probe tests where there are 2 disks per server for a total of 8
disks.  Specifically, swift.common.ring.utils.is_local_device() will
ignore the ports when the "my_port" argument is None.  Then,
object-replicator and object-reconstructor both set self.bind_port to
None if server_per_port is enabled.  Bonus improvement for IPv6
addresses in is_local_device().

This PR for vagrant-swift-all-in-one will aid in testing this patch:
https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/pull/16/

However, you can configure the SAIO to have different localhost IP

This new whataremyips() implementation combined with a little plumbing

in the ring.  In this mode, the parent swift-object-server process
continues to run as the original user (i.e. root if low-port binding
is required), binds to all ports as defined in the ring, and forks off
the specified number of workers per listen socket.  The child, per-port
servers drop privileges and behave pretty much how object-server workers
always have, except that because the ring has unique ports per disk, the
object-servers will only be handling requests for a single disk.  The
parent process detects dead servers and restarts them (with the correct
listen socket), starts missing servers when an updated ring file is
found with a device on the server with a new port, and kills extraneous
servers when their port is found to no longer be in the ring.  The ring
files are stat'ed at most every "ring_check_interval" seconds, as
configured in the object-server config (same default of 15s).

Immediately stopping all swift-object-worker processes still works by
sending the parent a SIGTERM.  Likewise, a SIGHUP to the parent process
still causes the parent process to close all listen sockets and exit,
allowing existing children to finish serving their existing requests.
The drop_privileges helper function now has an optional param to
suppress the setsid() call, which otherwise screws up the child workers'
process management.

The new class method RingData.load_devices() will load only the device
array from a serialized, gzipped ring file, retaining a reference to only
the returned array of device dicts.  This is used to keep the parent and
all forked off workers from unnecessarily having full copies of all
storage policy rings in memory.

A new helper method,
swift.common.storage_policy.all_bind_ports_for_node(), returns a set of
all device ports in all rings for a server (identified by its set of IP
addresses).  The function includes support for caching mtimes of the
ring files, so they are not opened more frequently than necessary (if
no rings have changed mtimes, then None is returned).  This is used by
swift-object-server when servers_per_port > 0 and takes advantage of
RingData.load_devices().

This patch includes enhancements to the probe tests and
object-replicator/object-reconstructor config plumbing to allow the
probe tests to work correctly both in the "normal" config (same IP but
unique ports for each SAIO "server") and a server-per-port setup where
each SAIO "server" must have a unique IP address and unique port per
disk within each "server".  The main probe tests only work with 4
servers and 4 disks, but you can see the difference in the rings for the
EC probe tests where there are 2 disks per server for a total of 8
disks.  Specifically, swift.common.ring.utils.is_local_device() will
ignore the ports when the "my_port" argument is None.  Then,
object-replicator and object-reconstructor both set self.bind_port to
None if server_per_port is enabled.  Bonus improvement for IPv6
addresses in is_local_device().

This PR for vagrant-swift-all-in-one will aid in testing this patch:
https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/pull/16/

Also allow SAIO to answer is_local_device() better; common SAIO setups
have multiple "servers" all on the same host with different ports for
the different "servers" (which happen to match the IPs specified in the
rings for the devices on each of those "servers").

However, you can configure the SAIO to have different localhost IP
addresses (e.g. 127.0.0.1, 127.0.0.2, etc.) in the ring and in the
servers' config files' bind_ip setting.

This new whataremyips() implementation combined with a little plumbing
allows is_local_device() to accurately answer, even on an SAIO.

In the default case (an unspecified bind_ip defaults to '0.0.0.0') as
well as an explict "bind to everything" like '0.0.0.0' or '::',
whataremyips() behaves as it always has, returning all IP addresses for
the server.

Also updated probe tests to handle each "server" in the SAIO having a
unique IP address.

For some (noisy) benchmarks that show servers_per_port=X is at least as
good as the same number of "normal" workers:
https://gist.github.com/dbishop/c214f89ca708a6b1624a#file-summary-md

DocImpact

continues to run as the original user (i.e. root if low-port binding
is required), binds to all ports as defined in the ring, and forks off
the specified number of workers per listen socket.  The child, per-port
servers drop privileges and behave pretty much how object-server workers
always have, except that because the ring has unique ports per disk, the
object-servers will only be handling requests for a single disk.  The
parent process detects dead servers and restarts them (with the correct
listen socket), starts missing servers when an updated ring file is
found with a device on the server with a new port, and kills extraneous
servers when their port is found to no longer be in the ring.  The ring
files are stat'ed at most every "ring_check_interval" seconds, as
configured in the object-server config (same default of 15s).

Immediately stopping all swift-object-worker processes still works by
sending the parent a SIGTERM.  Likewise, a SIGHUP to the parent process
still causes the parent process to close all listen sockets and exit,
allowing existing children to finish serving their existing requests.
The drop_privileges helper function now has an optional param to
suppress the setsid() call, which otherwise screws up the child workers'
process management.

The class method RingData.load() can be told to only load the ring
metadata (i.e. everything except replica2part2dev_id) with the optional
kwarg, header_only=True.  This is used to keep the parent and all
forked off workers from unnecessarily having full copies of all storage
policy rings in memory.

A new helper class, swift.common.storage_policy.BindPortsCache,
provides a method to return a set of all device ports in all rings for
the server on which it is instantiated (identified by its set of IP
addresses).  The BindPortsCache instance will track mtimes of ring
files, so they are not opened more frequently than necessary.

This patch includes enhancements to the probe tests and
object-replicator/object-reconstructor config plumbing to allow the
probe tests to work correctly both in the "normal" config (same IP but
unique ports for each SAIO "server") and a server-per-port setup where
each SAIO "server" must have a unique IP address and unique port per
disk within each "server".  The main probe tests only work with 4
servers and 4 disks, but you can see the difference in the rings for the
EC probe tests where there are 2 disks per server for a total of 8
disks.  Specifically, swift.common.ring.utils.is_local_device() will
ignore the ports when the "my_port" argument is None.  Then,
object-replicator and object-reconstructor both set self.bind_port to
None if server_per_port is enabled.  Bonus improvement for IPv6
addresses in is_local_device().

This PR for vagrant-swift-all-in-one will aid in testing this patch:
https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/pull/16/

Also allow SAIO to answer is_local_device() better; common SAIO setups
have multiple "servers" all on the same host with different ports for
the different "servers" (which happen to match the IPs specified in the
rings for the devices on each of those "servers").

However, you can configure the SAIO to have different localhost IP
addresses (e.g. 127.0.0.1, 127.0.0.2, etc.) in the ring and in the
servers' config files' bind_ip setting.

This new whataremyips() implementation combined with a little plumbing
allows is_local_device() to accurately answer, even on an SAIO.

In the default case (an unspecified bind_ip defaults to '0.0.0.0') as
well as an explict "bind to everything" like '0.0.0.0' or '::',
whataremyips() behaves as it always has, returning all IP addresses for
the server.

Also updated probe tests to handle each "server" in the SAIO having a
unique IP address.

For some (noisy) benchmarks that show servers_per_port=X is at least as
good as the same number of "normal" workers:
https://gist.github.com/dbishop/c214f89ca708a6b1624a#file-summary-md

Benchmarks showing the benefits of I/O isolation with a small number of
slow disks:
https://gist.github.com/dbishop/fd0ab067babdecfb07ca#file-results-md

If you were wondering what the overhead of threads_per_disk looks like:
https://gist.github.com/dbishop/1d14755fedc86a161718#file-tabular_results-md

DocImpact

Change-Id: I2239a4000b41a7e7cc53465ce794af49d44796c6

commit_message:
Allow 1+ object-servers-per-disk deployment

Enabled by a new > 0 integer config value, "servers_per_port" in the
[DEFAULT] config section for object-server and/or replication server
configs.  The setting's integer value determines how many different
object-server workers handle requests for any single unique local port
in the ring.  In this mode, the parent swift-object-server process
continues to run as the original user (i.e. root if low-port binding
is required), binds to all ports as defined in the ring, and forks off
the specified number of workers per listen socket.  The child, per-port
servers drop privileges and behave pretty much how object-server workers
always have, except that because the ring has unique ports per disk, the
object-servers will only be handling requests for a single disk.  The
parent process detects dead servers and restarts them (with the correct
listen socket), starts missing servers when an updated ring file is
found with a device on the server with a new port, and kills extraneous
servers when their port is found to no longer be in the ring.  The ring
files are stat'ed at most every "ring_check_interval" seconds, as
configured in the object-server config (same default of 15s).

Immediately stopping all swift-object-worker processes still works by
sending the parent a SIGTERM.  Likewise, a SIGHUP to the parent process
still causes the parent process to close all listen sockets and exit,
allowing existing children to finish serving their existing requests.
The drop_privileges helper function now has an optional param to
suppress the setsid() call, which otherwise screws up the child workers'
process management.

The class method RingData.load() can be told to only load the ring
metadata (i.e. everything except replica2part2dev_id) with the optional
kwarg, header_only=True.  This is used to keep the parent and all
forked off workers from unnecessarily having full copies of all storage
policy rings in memory.

A new helper class, swift.common.storage_policy.BindPortsCache,
provides a method to return a set of all device ports in all rings for
the server on which it is instantiated (identified by its set of IP
addresses).  The BindPortsCache instance will track mtimes of ring
files, so they are not opened more frequently than necessary.

This patch includes enhancements to the probe tests and
object-replicator/object-reconstructor config plumbing to allow the
probe tests to work correctly both in the "normal" config (same IP but
unique ports for each SAIO "server") and a server-per-port setup where
each SAIO "server" must have a unique IP address and unique port per
disk within each "server".  The main probe tests only work with 4
servers and 4 disks, but you can see the difference in the rings for the
EC probe tests where there are 2 disks per server for a total of 8
disks.  Specifically, swift.common.ring.utils.is_local_device() will
ignore the ports when the "my_port" argument is None.  Then,
object-replicator and object-reconstructor both set self.bind_port to
None if server_per_port is enabled.  Bonus improvement for IPv6
addresses in is_local_device().

This PR for vagrant-swift-all-in-one will aid in testing this patch:
https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/pull/16/

Also allow SAIO to answer is_local_device() better; common SAIO setups
have multiple "servers" all on the same host with different ports for
the different "servers" (which happen to match the IPs specified in the
rings for the devices on each of those "servers").

However, you can configure the SAIO to have different localhost IP
addresses (e.g. 127.0.0.1, 127.0.0.2, etc.) in the ring and in the
servers' config files' bind_ip setting.

This new whataremyips() implementation combined with a little plumbing
allows is_local_device() to accurately answer, even on an SAIO.

In the default case (an unspecified bind_ip defaults to '0.0.0.0') as
well as an explict "bind to everything" like '0.0.0.0' or '::',
whataremyips() behaves as it always has, returning all IP addresses for
the server.

Also updated probe tests to handle each "server" in the SAIO having a
unique IP address.

For some (noisy) benchmarks that show servers_per_port=X is at least as
good as the same number of "normal" workers:
https://gist.github.com/dbishop/c214f89ca708a6b1624a#file-summary-md

Benchmarks showing the benefits of I/O isolation with a small number of
slow disks:
https://gist.github.com/dbishop/fd0ab067babdecfb07ca#file-results-md

If you were wondering what the overhead of threads_per_disk looks like:
https://gist.github.com/dbishop/1d14755fedc86a161718#file-tabular_results-md

commit_message:
Add project_id to Secret model

The approach of having a separate table for the Secret-Project
associations is being deprecated in favor of having a foreign key to the
Project model (as described in the blueprint). This commit is an initial
step towards that goal, so the following was done:

* Add the project_id to the Secret model.
* Enhance the logic in the repositories and plugin.resources in order to
  first search that new field, and if it doesn't work, fall back to the
  previous approach.
* Added the necessary code for the project_id to be filled for the
  secret.

Note that the association table approach still works and will be removed
in a subsequent commit.

blueprint data-remove-tenant-secret-assoc

Change-Id: Icabeb5b3fc2e5aaa8c0c4fc4dfb5aae7405c4e2c

commit_message:
Gate at RST line length of 79 chars

With this patch, the RST files have no line longer than 79 chars -
as discussed on the docs mailing list - and we
can gate on it. Previously this limit was 100 chars.

Change-Id: I23f550db81e9264649d0444f5f1ba1be0d6d343d

commit_message:
Fix the ThreadMgr mocking in test_stack_create_max_unlimited

use the helper method _test_stack_create() as it correctly mocks
the ThreadMgr. Otherwise this runs in the background and the test
deletes the stack while it is running in the background.

Change-Id: Ia64a09c93cf5414b0943fc9495c435355b5645fc
Closes-bug: #1432936

commit_message:
Make the objects behave more consistently

1. don't return DB models from the objects API
   (only return Objects)
2. delete shouldn't return anything
3. update_and_save should return the refreshed object.

Note: there is still some inconsistency in what is returned by
update_by_id() some return an object and some return a bool.

Related-bug: #1432936
Change-Id: I1a0a38773d4fc4a62af5e0a98076396f39187b6c

commit_message:
Not all exceptions from remote stacks are internal exceptions

The code in stack_resource assumed all exceptions raised in the
remote stack were from heat/common/exceptions.py but oslo messaging
also raises exceptions (timeout).

Change-Id: I91e1497ebf731a69fa86a574b42cccfe59430df1
Closes-bug: #1459837

commit_message:
Fix tox -e py34

* Add requirements-py3.txt: get the master branch of glance_store from
  github until a new release of glance_store including all my Python 3
  fixed will be released.
* Add test-requirements-py3.txt: remove qpid-python and MySQL-python
  (not compatible with Python 3), add PyMySQL
* tox.ini: add py34 test environment running tests with testtools.run.
  Use a whitelist of tests which are known to pass on Python 3.4. testr
  cannot be used because it loads all tests, and not all tests are
  compatible with Python 3.4 yet.

Change-Id: If19af8351e9497db26c9cd62393d22d2043a3903

commit_message:
Fix firewall remove router

Firewall remove router doesn't work because method "get_new_router_id" of
RemoveRouterFromFirewall doesn't return the right router ids. This patch
fix it by only return router ids after removing the router ids we chosed,
also fix the test module of firewall.

Change-Id: Icb233b704aacc7bef7f9acf0481202e3598fce65
Closes-Bug: #1467208

commit_message:
Tintri driver to manage existing backend storage objects

* Manage existing volume
* Get size of volume to be managed
* Unmanage volume

* Add tintri_api_version configuration option
* Make tintri_server_username configuration option required

DocImpact

Change-Id: I87c1213f9b9413cb7a0d95f4a75ffd9165baf1b3

LGTM to keep v2.1 API compatible'}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2015-02-25 11:26:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-02-25 12:43:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-02 22:14:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-03-02 22:36:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

So I'm a bit confused now, why do we need 2 gating jobs for this in addition to the bazillion other v2 jobs. If v2 is deprecated why not just make v2.1 the default for testing and move the v2 job to experimental/periodic. I'm all for making v2.1 the thing we use and test with, I just want an answer to why we need to be testing both gating."}, {'account_id': 8556, 'date': '2015-03-03 05:13:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Matthew - That is good point to make v2.1 default for testing. Just one concern.
Now v2 is 'SUPPORTED' (I2c5e6612db4a792f1950f53c0bc69617e47b0fff) and /v2 endpoint still point to v2 code base. After some time, once we have full confidence on v2.1 then, /v2 also start pointing to v2.1 code base. Then we should only test v2.1  but till then (/v2 endpoint points to v2 code) I think we should have v2 job too.

At this time, if making v2 jobs experimental/periodic then, there might be chance to accidentally merge v2 back incompatible changes.

Need opinion if i am wrong (personally I like v2.1 to make default :))"}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-03-03 18:52:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm just talking from my perspective of the tempest queue where we already have ~20 jobs. I'm not keen on duplicating the job set for master with 2 nova api versions. I was on the fence about having 1 job for this but was fine with it as a temporary measure to bring things up. I think what I'm getting at is you guys really just need to pick one as the primary API (which I would assume is v2.1 at this point) and make that what we test everywhere by default, and leave v2 as the secondary api.

We can verify the secondary with periodic/experimental jobs, sure that will expose a risk for landing something which breaks the other api, but that's the tradeoff. I'm just not convinced that duplicating every current gating configuration for v2.1 so we cover both apis at the same time is the right approach here.

The other aspect to consider is if we make the v2 api the secondary then we'll also still be testing it on the stable branches for what that's worth. So at least tempest won't be able to land breaking v2 api changes even if on master it only tests v2.1 in the gate.

But, either way I don't feel strongly enough on this to -1. I just wanted to outline my concerns that this is a slippery slope."}, {'account_id': 6316, 'date': '2015-03-04 00:38:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'd like to hear from other api devs that they have a testing strategy that addresses Matt's concerns if not in the short term then in the long term."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-11 17:01:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-03-12 00:23:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Matthew's point seems reasonable, so how about the following?

This patch
* remove (gate|check)-tempest-dsvm-nova-v21-neutron-full
* rename (gate|check)-tempest-dsvm-full to tempest-dsvm-nova-v20, and specify "Nova v2.0 API" option.

After that, post a devstack patch for switching default Nova API to "Nova v2.1 API".

We can test Nova v2.1 API as the default API without additional jobs.'}, {'account_id': 8556, 'date': '2015-03-12 01:35:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Ken'ichi - That's looks perfect for me.

Just 1 idea,
how about making compute endpoint default to v21 in tempest. And then let devstack run all jobs for v21 without alerting any endpoint except nova v2.0 job (renamed one as you mentioned) which it will redirect from /v2.1  to /v2."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-03-12 01:42:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Tempest is branchless now, so it seems difficult to control v2/v2.1 endpoint in Tempest side because of stable/icehouse and stable/juno.

devstack is not branchless and it is controlling this kind of changes between releases.'}, {'account_id': 8556, 'date': '2015-03-12 02:21:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

ahh yes.'}, {'account_id': 8556, 'date': '2015-03-12 08:37:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Below patches makes the v21 default. Please have look
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163718/
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163725/
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163731/'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-03-27 00:51:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I proposed https://review.openstack.org/168193 related to this patch.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-06-19 20:12:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

is this patch still needed?'}, {'account_id': 8556, 'date': '2015-06-22 01:41:21.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Not needed now. Should to run v2.1 as default in gate.'}]

commit_message:
Make 'tempest-dsvm-nova-v21-neutron-full' job voting

Nova V2.1 API is now current API
(I2c5e6612db4a792f1950f53c0bc69617e47b0fff).
And 'tempest-dsvm-nova-v21-neutron-full' job is passing
(Idd585419ba588bbad655c2f5e0594f9ada1b2462) on gate.

Now this job should be changed from non-voting to voting job
to avoid any accidental or backward incompatible change in
Nova V2.1 API.

This patch makes that job as voting and also adding this job
on gate pipeline.

Change-Id: I0e2220a9632333e5b8ee8e5d999af26594a984e1

commit_message:
Fix tuskar path

Tuskar requires /v2 in the endpoint path now.  This was done in the
incubator setup-endpoints but apparently not in os-cloud-config.

Change-Id: I791202f1076f9984c27ecf70bd6dad665b5c7a55

commit_message:
make heat-manage a console_script entry point

pbr has extra sauce for correctly making installed cli tools not do
unneeded pkg_resources metadata checks (that can only end in tears) if
those scripts are installed via the console_script entry
point. heat-manage looks like it is ready to be used this way.

Other scripts should be converted in the future to avoid erroneous
errors due to library metadata mismatch, which these tools should not
care about.

Change-Id: Ibfd54e7b1bae700e4fb49a32e5bf7c00d1f104d9

commit_message:
Web Interface for Magnum in Horizon

Currently there is no way for a user to interact with Magnum through a web based
user interface, as they are used to doing with other OpenStack components. This
implementation aims to introduce this interface as an extension of Horizon (the
OpenStack Dashboard) and expose all the features of Magnum in a way familiar to
users.

Implements: blueprint magnum-horizon-plugin

Change-Id: I832ee1fdf0c9b2f1ece8b01329d5c7f5bec8ae3c

@Duncan Thomas, Soren Hansen, Tom Barron:

Here is the use-case

Currently we can set quota for a tenant, as well as number of volumes a tenant can create.
However, there is a need to limit maximum size of a volume to levels that the storage 
infrastructure can handle.

Example: If volumes are based on Linux LVM, the local disks are used to create volumes for the VMs.
We need to limit the maximum size of volume so that a given number if VMs can be created on the host.

Setting a maximum limit on size of a volume also prevents a tenant from creating large volumes that
have not been tested and certified to satisfy SLA objectives.

Examples of performance criteria could include time to take a backup, snapshot, etc.

With such a limit in place, a provider could test the storage infrastructure at different volume sizes and
set the limit accordingly.'}, {'account_id': 9003, 'date': '2015-06-04 12:04:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Thanks for the use case.  I agree that it matches what
you have implemented and will remove my -1 when you
address Soren's latest inline remark and get pylint to pass."}, {'account_id': 15254, 'date': '2015-06-04 14:57:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-04 15:58:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

I can't fully understand this change and the reason for it

"Describe why a change is being made."

It would be good to briefly explain the use case that motivates the change (as you've done in the review notes).

"The first commit line is the most important."

I made a suggestion inline, but you may have a better idea than that.  In any case, I think it can be improved.

"Do not assume the code is self-evident/self-documenting."

It isn't self-evident what is the significance of the -1 default value. Is it an invalid value?  A no-quota value?
Knowing this will help the reviewer consider whether current
unit test coverage is enough, as well as just understanding the impact to administrators if they don't set this configuration.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-09 11:23:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

This feature allows admin to set volume size limit for a tenant.
Get default value for volume size limit via config.
The defaults will either come from the default values set in the quota configuration
option or via cinder.conf if the user has configured
default values for quotas there.

The per_volume_size_limit defaults to -1 always
unless changed in cinder.conf by admin

commit_message:
Add config option to set max_volume_size_limit

There is a need to limit maximum size of a volume to levels
that the storage infrastructure can handle.
Setting a maximum limit on size of a volume also prevents
a tenant from creating large volumes that have not been tested
and certified to satisfy SLA objectives.

This feature allows admin to set volume size limit for a tenant.
Get default value for volume size limit via config.
The defaults will either come from the default values
set in the quota configuration option or via cinder.conf
if the user has configured default values for quotas there.

The per_volume_size_limit defaults to -1["No Limit"] always
unless changed in cinder.conf by admin

Change-Id: Ieb5c087ca7a33d22342470ea790a0c979a6244ea
Implements: blueprint cinder-quota-define-per-volume

Actually no, we may need path_args to come through the BaseProxy._list method. We won't be able to get that from self.

The _get_resource() method gets passed path_args.  They should be passed into the resource.  Not sure if that works.

I'm thinking about compute.server_ips() -- right now it takes no parms, but it has to be able to take a server.Server instance or id in order to be hooked up properly. commit_message:
Add path_args when invoking Resource.list() from proxy layer

Currently, path_args parameter is not given when invoking list
method of resource module from proxy layer. However, without this
arguments, url can't be generated correctly if path_args is defined
in resource's base_url. This patch tried to fix this issue.

Change-Id: Id381867a83362f4e2a5e44004023a4d749398476

commit_message:
Continue to check if nova task is in progress

Continue to check whether the nova server is deleted
completed if nova task is in progress. There is an attribute
'OS-EXT-STS: task_state' which showing task state in nova.

Closes-Bug: #1463716
(cherry picked from commit ab350ce095927037a1d0a8a552fa2b2dfac67d0a)

Conflicts:
	heat/engine/clients/os/nova.py

Change-Id: I64e5319bceeeaead064a7ee062906d707d0a333a

commit_message:
Add support for configuration file

This corresponds to the new following option

  --config file_name

Multiple actions can be specified in the configuration file
and will be executed in a single freezer run.

Change-Id: I5b949420df59b6f15ed43007927535435c4615ef
Implements: blueprint config-file

commit_message:
Update version for Liberty

Update the version for Liberty, switching from date-based versioning
to pre-versioning using SemVer. See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/065211.html
and
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067082.html
for details.

Any references to future versions are updated to match the new
semver style versions.

Change-Id: I6a35fa0dda798fad93b804d00a46af80f08d475c

commit_message:
Add api support for jobs

removes distinction between actions and configs in the api

The v1/jobs endpoint is the single point of access to the api
to store, search and retrieve operating instruction about
a single freezer run.

optional scheduling informations can be added to a job to
allow for future/recurrent job execution.

removes api endpoints
  - v1/actions
  - v1/configs

adds api endpoints:
  - v1/jobs

Implements blueprint: freezer-api-jobs

Change-Id: Ideeef14dfccd21ddd10b4faa438124c04d2e1ff8

commit_message:
Adds FC and ISCSI Cinder drivers for Lenovo Storage Arrays

These drivers depend upon DotHill Cinder drivers.
Using inheritance, we are able to reuse a lot of
DotHill cinder drivers source code.

Change-Id: Ica8631d6954898dbd90a71cc78625bb2aa3b5632
Co-Authored-By: Gauvain Pocentek<gauvain.pocentek@objectif-libre.com>
Implements: blueprint lenovo-fc-iscsi-cinder-driver

It's generally best to leave this alone."}, {'account_id': 124, 'date': '2015-03-10 10:25:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The sheepdog test job needs to be run on the 'devstack-trusty' node because the  sheepdog package of Ubuntu precise is too outdated to be used with OpenStack.
Is there better way to exclude the 'devstack-precise' node for sheepdog tests, or should we modify the sheepdog plugin so that the test job can run on both 'devstack-precise' and 'devstack-trusty'?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-14 08:34:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

is this patch still needed or should it get abandoned?'}, {'account_id': 124, 'date': '2015-06-21 17:08:06.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

It seems that all the sheepdog tests have been run on the trusty nodes - it has been working as I want without this patch. Although I'm not sure the reason, there is no problem with the current configuration so I'll abandon this change."}]

commit_message:
Add node parameter to the devstack-plugin template

This is necessary since the sheepdog plugin works only on ubuntu trusty.

Change-Id: Ia64c5127dee6ecd92f449126508f422d41a52e08

commit_message:
devstack: OVN is now in master OVS branch

Per email to the ovs-dev mailing list [1], OVN has been merged
into the master branch of OVS. This patch updates the default
branch used when pulling OVN to reflect the new location.

[1] http://openvswitch.org/pipermail/dev/2015-June/056599.html

Change-Id: I4e3ab54a6264744f6234ee538eb1165099fd9df7
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Convert RabbitMQ active/active doc to RST

I did not convert the active/passive doc as I believe that
is being deprecated.

Change-Id: I417fc0d0949905fc656217e621c7064ae70ef551

RST formatting of commands

-Experimenting with the usage of
root prompt and gen'ed output.
-Dollar sign for command prompt
produces correct output.
-Moved last note directive to improve

commit_message:
Create iSCSI lio portals with right IPs and port

Currently lioadm helper creates portals with fixed IP addresses 0.0.0.0
and ::0 and also uses fixed standard port 3260 instead of using store
configuration (iscsi_ip_address, iscsi_secondary_ip_addresses,
iscsi_port) from the configuration as it should.

This could lead to problems if a different port was defined in the
configuration as the target would be available only on 3260 and other
services would look for it at configured port.

With this fix we now create the right portals with the right port.

Since now we pass list of ips and port to helpers cxt helper has also
been updated to use these parameters instead of going directly to the
configuration.

Change-Id: I77e8865b1f015a9fa155f2b4552a5d9c27f5e122
Closes-Bug: #1425875
(cherry picked from commit 3abc1d2f63730638abc0344989ccb277b8212642)
Conflicts:
	cinder/cmd/rtstool.py
	cinder/tests/targets/test_cxt_driver.py
	cinder/tests/targets/test_iet_driver.py
	cinder/tests/targets/test_lio_driver.py
	cinder/tests/unit/targets/targets_fixture.py

commit_message:
Deprecate unused exceptions

Deprecate the following unused exceptions:
* VMwareDriverConfigurationException
* UseLinkedCloneConfigurationFault
* MissingParameter

The above exceptions are specific to VMware Nova driver and
should be moved to Nova code base.

Change-Id: I74482d6ac436fbea4383a197f24704bc3d033076

commit_message:
Raise VimFaultException for unknown faults

Currently VMwareDriverException is raised for unknown
VIM faults. Sometimes clients may need to handle such
faults. Therefore it is better if we throw
VimFaultException with the fault_list set to the relevant
VIM fault class name.

Change-Id: I97d93ceaa82514d029fff87f1c5ad942895d8940

The concept of "compute" node and "network" node is an artificial one.  The terms are used for convinience when discussing openstack but in reality there is no technical difference between the two. 
i.e. I can make a "compute" node a "network" node if I decide to run snat on it, or any of the other network services, like dhcp or ha-router, etc... 
We should not introduce this categorization of the nodes into the code base. The separation of router classes should be based on functionality (ha, dvr, snat, etc..) NOT on physical location of the router ("compute ndoe", "network node", "my aunts node" :), etc...'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-05-27 19:26:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Well, the router classes split as proposed in this patch are about functionality, not location. DVR routers have two components: The distributed part, and the centralized part. Sometimes a L3 agent can configure only the distributed part, sometimes both. I think we should model the code according to that, and that means separate classes.'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-05-27 23:46:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(6 comments)

Mostly, I think you're on exactly the right path.  I just wanted to be sure that we agree on a few points.  I also agree with @Adolfo about how to split the class but I think what you have is pretty close."}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-05-28 05:45:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(5 comments)

I agree with Adolfo and Carl comments about the names, the problem i had is i still wanted to reflect this is a Dvr mode and DistributedDvrRouter doesnt sound right :)

So maybe DistributedRouterDVRMode ?

Any other suggestions?'}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-05-31 05:41:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-05-31 06:00:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(12 comments)

Replied for all the comments, in general this patch is logically correct and "pretty safe".
It involves file name changes which also involves complicated merges, i prefer to get this first step merged first and then handle the rest.

Also there are still unresolved issues that i need to address, there are some critical points and i don't think it will be smart to address everything in one patch.

To Assaf, the idea in this patch is not to extract all the SNAT features, as some of the code you commented about is for the virtual router namespace and relates to the SNAT ports there (additional interface created for each subnet automatically in snat_dvr mode).
This code also happens in the compute node.

The idea is just to extract the code that happens on the network node which relates to the SNAT namespace.

Also there are some points which we can discuss in the meeting for the next steps but i really want to first do this extraction (and not block other work on the already crowded router) and get it merged.'}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-06-14 17:17:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 15.'}, {'account_id': 15894, 'date': '2015-06-14 17:17:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

@Gal: test_agent.py should be split up, so that tests that target the DvrLocalRouter class should be moved to the appropriate file. I added a few examples of tests that I think can be moved as is. I think a bunch more can be moved. The importance is that it's very confusing for new contributors to come onboard. How are they supposed to find these tests when they're all just bunched up in one gigantic test class? Since tests often serve as implicit documentation, and because when you want to add a test you really want to copy/paste a similar one, it's important for us to place tests according to the code they target. In this case, a lot of the tests in test_agent target code in the DvrLocalRouter class and should be moved accordingly.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-25 12:41:23.000000000', 'message': 'Decomposite DVR CSNAT L3 Agent from Compute Node L3 Agent

Currently the same dvr router class is used both by the L3 Agent
in the compute nodes that is responsible for the virtual routers
namespace and the fip namespace and also used by the centralized
SNAT L3 Agent in the network node.
This is the first step to decomposite the two into different
classes.

Next steps:
1) Remove is_snat_host validations and change dvr_router file name
2) Align unit/functional tests
3) Create the correct class in the L3 agent depending on the host
   address
4) Consider non inheritance model

Change-Id: I581a097b9e7c49f20d0eb0e4ca66a25e90d9511b
Partial-Bug: #1458541

Partial-Bug: #1458541
'}, {'created': '2015-05-26 04:56:44.000000000', 'message': 'Decomposite DVR CSNAT L3 Agent from Compute Node L3 Agent

Currently the same dvr router class is used both by the L3 Agent
in the compute nodes that is responsible for the virtual routers
namespace and the fip namespace and also used by the centralized
SNAT L3 Agent in the network node.
This is the first step for decomposition the two into different
classes.

The above means that we have one class of DVR router which is used
for two jobs (the virtual router namespace wiring and the fips wiring
in the compute node in one hand and the centralized snat wiring in the
other)
The end goal of this patch is to separate the two into different classes
which will also help maintaining it and also help projects that want
to use one but not the other (for example only use the centralized
SNAT behaviour with there own DVR implementation)

Next steps:
1) Remove is_snat_host validations and change dvr_router file name
2) Align unit/functional tests
3) Create the correct class in the L3 agent depending on the host
   address
4) Align with HA+DVR patch
5) Consider non inheritance model

Change-Id: I581a097b9e7c49f20d0eb0e4ca66a25e90d9511b
Partial-Bug: #1458541

'}, {'created': '2015-06-02 15:13:38.000000000', 'message': 'Decomposite DVR CSNAT L3 Agent from Compute Node L3 Agent

Currently the same dvr router class is used both by the L3 Agent
in the compute nodes that is responsible for the virtual routers
namespace and the fip namespace and also used by the centralized
SNAT L3 Agent in the network node.
This is the first step to decomposite the two into different
classes.

The above means that we have one class of DVR router which is used
for two jobs (the virtual router namespace wiring and the fips wiring
in the compute node in one hand and the centralized snat wiring in the other)
The end goal of this patch is to separate the two into different classes
which will also help maintaining it and also help projects that want
to use one but not the other (for example only use the centralized
SNAT behaviour with there own DVR implementation)

Next steps:
1) Remove is_snat_host validations and change dvr_router file name
2) Align unit/functional tests
3) Create the correct class in the L3 agent depending on the host
   address
4) Align with HA+DVR patch
5) Consider non inheritance model

Change-Id: I581a097b9e7c49f20d0eb0e4ca66a25e90d9511b
Partial-Bug: #1458541

node.

commit_message:
Decompose DVR CSNAT L3 Agent from Compute Node L3 Agent

Currently the same dvr router class is used both by the L3 Agent
in the compute nodes that is responsible for the virtual routers
namespace and the fip namespace and also used by the centralized
SNAT L3 Agent in the network node.
This is the first step to decompose the two into different
classes.

The above means that we have one class of DVR router which is used
for two jobs (the virtual router namespace wiring and the fips wiring
in the compute node in one hand and the centralized snat wiring in the other)
The end goal of this patch is to separate the two into different classes
which will also help maintaining it and also help projects that want
to use one but not the other (for example only use the centralized
SNAT behaviour with there own DVR implementation)

Change-Id: I581a097b9e7c49f20d0eb0e4ca66a25e90d9511b
Partial-Bug: #1458541
Partially-Implements: blueprint dvr-router-code-decompose

commit_message:
Fix 'unsupported locale setting' errors in init-runonce

Keystone requires a valid LC_ALL environment variable to be set, if left
empty the following output is shown:

"""
$ tools/init-runonce
Downloading glance image.
Creating glance image.
[=============================>] 100%
<snip>
Configuring neutron.
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
unsupported locale setting
Could not find any suitable endpoint. Correct region?
<snip>
"""

A similar problem occurred in devstack
(https://bugs.launchpad.net/devstack/+bug/1249131), apply the same patch
they use to to sanitize language settings
(https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/blob/master/stack.sh#L27).

Closes-Bug: #1466548

Change-Id: I8e86a4466181d6dd1c1749915c1c43521af805b7

commit_message:
libvirt: safe_decode xml for i18n logging

The xml argument passed to _create_domain can be a utf-8 encoded string
which causes a UnicodeDecodeError when it is substituted into the _LE
unicode translated message. Safely decoding the xml argument before
attempting to substitute it into the error message avoids the
UnicodeDecodeError.

(cherry picked from commit 96a2283c1a07f0298c57f57d8c4112c1c33b6128)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py
	nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py

Change to strutils (instead of encodeutils) and test is located in
"tests/" instead of "tests/unit/".

Closes-Bug: #1453274
Change-Id: I4cf1836f4ca9097f7c6d98c5212a14d24111fe67

'}, {'created': '2015-05-18 12:26:51.000000000', 'message': 'Add 3 tests with vcenter and nodes with multiroles:

- vcenter_nodes_with_multiroles_cindervmdk_and_cinder
	Scenario:
            1. Create cluster with vCenter support
            2. Add 6 nodes with following roles:
                controller + Cinder
                controller + CinderVMDK
                controller + Cinder + CinderVMDK
                compute + Cinder
                compute + CinderVMDK
                compute + Cinder + CinderVMDK
            3. Set Nova-Network VlanManager as a network backend
            4. Deploy the cluster
            5. Run network verification
            6. Run OSTF

- vcenter_ceph_nodes_with_multiroles_cindervmdk_and cephosd
	Scenario:
            1. Create cluster with vCenter support
            2. Add 6 nodes with following roles:
                controller + CephOSD
                controller + CinderVMDK
                controller + CephOSD + CinderVMDK
                compute + CephOSD
                compute + CinderVMDK
                compute + CephOSD + CinderVMDK
            3. Set Nova-Network VlanManager as a network backend
            4. Deploy the cluster
            5. Run network verification
            6. Run OSTF

- vcenter_ceilometer_nodes_with_multiroles_cindervmdk_and_mongodb
	Scenario:
            1. Create cluster with vCenter support
            2. Add 6 nodes with following roles:
                controller + MongoDB + Cinder
                controller + MongoDB + CinderVMDK
                controller + MongoDB + Cinder + CinderVMDK
                compute + MongoDB + Cinder
                compute + MongoDB + CinderVMDK
                compute + MongoDB + Cinder + CinderVMDK
            3. Set Nova-Network VlanManager as a network backend
            4. Deploy the cluster
            5. Run network verification
            6. Run OSTF

Change-Id: I2255344f5b67d598cd1a0a126b0fee6edce20012
Closes-bug: #1453082

commit_message:
Add 3 tests with vcenter and nodes with multiroles:

- vcenter_nodes_with_multiroles_cindervmdk_and_cinder
	Scenario:
            1. Create cluster with vCenter support
            2. Add 6 nodes with following roles:
                controller + Cinder
                controller + CinderVMDK
                controller + Cinder + CinderVMDK
                compute + Cinder
                compute + CinderVMDK
                compute + Cinder + CinderVMDK
            3. Set Nova-Network VlanManager as a network backend
            4. Deploy the cluster
            5. Run network verification
            6. Run OSTF

- vcenter_ceph_nodes_with_multiroles_cindervmdk_and cephosd
	Scenario:
            1. Create cluster with vCenter support
            2. Add 6 nodes with following roles:
                controller + CephOSD
                controller + CinderVMDK
                controller + CephOSD + CinderVMDK
                compute + CephOSD
                compute + CinderVMDK
                compute + CephOSD + CinderVMDK
            3. Set Nova-Network VlanManager as a network backend
            4. Deploy the cluster
            5. Run network verification
            6. Run OSTF

- vcenter_ceilometer_nodes_with_multiroles_cindervmdk_and_mongodb
	Scenario:
            1. Create cluster with vCenter support
            2. Add 3 nodes with following roles:
                controller + MongoDB + Cinder
                controller + MongoDB + CinderVMDK
                controller + MongoDB + Cinder + CinderVMDK
            3. Set Nova-Network VlanManager as a network backend
            4. Deploy the cluster
            5. Run network verification
            6. Run OSTF
- change platform_test to tests_platform in 'vcenter_ceilometer'
Change-Id: I2255344f5b67d598cd1a0a126b0fee6edce20012
Closes-bug: #1453082, #1466861

commit_message:
Fix packaging issue by removing ${python:Depends}

Debian `control` file establishes the dependencies of the package. One
function that can be used is the ${python:Depends}, which will create
`python-*` dependencies based on `requirements.txt`. So it was defining
`python-oslo.log` as dependency automatically.

Problem is `python-oslo.log` does not exist as a package in Debian,
correct name is `python-oslo-log`. So better to remove the
${python:Depends} and define all the dependencies explicitly.

Change-Id: Idab8899e5fe47c1c9b7397ede68c2dbb2b7c884d

commit_message:
Validate subnet for pool/vip properly

There was a validation to prevent VIP and Pool that belong in the same
subnet to be created. This was wrong because LB would work even if they
are in the same subnet as long as the client is not in the same subnet
as the VIP.  The validation should have occurred only when there as a
health monitor associated with a pool  This patch implementes the
correct validation.

Change-Id: Ib2dd24048a6badedb8baf7b3625d47f0e87f34b2
Fixes: MNP-154

commit_message:
Port common.crypt to Python 3

* Replace chr(0) with b'\0'
* Use ''.join(chr(x) ...) with b''.join(six.int2byte(x) ...)
* Replace str with six.binary_type
* test_misc: replace '' with b'' in plaintext_list, plaintext must be
  bytes
* tox: add test_misc to Python 3.4

Change-Id: I5f3bed2c664181210b76b1a5b62eacda47420e7f

commit_message:
Port api.versions to Python 3

With this change, tox -e py34 now pass:

* On Python 3, jsonutils.dumps() returns Unicode on Python 3, whereas
  HTTP body is bytes: encode JSON to UTF-8
* Fix tox -e py34, but only run glance.tests.unit.test_versions

Later, more tests will be added tox -e py34, and a voting py34 gate will
be added to ensure that no Python 3 regression is added back.

Depends-on: I66b7d6053643e82d9c11af568190d82ffe7f385e
Depends-on: I7e5a24453cf837391e1fad73b7bb0c0fbd8963e2
Change-Id: I8a546fcfa3b8132885d2f8f9bbbf999ca0500e31

commit_message:
Revert "Remove unneeded package subscription-manager"

It seems that this package somehow brings python-ethtools to container.
So let put it back and find a way to remove it properly without removing
required packages.

Closes-Bug: #1467107

This reverts commit 656f39cca441e1593b7ea536ce7a35e10cf48884.

Change-Id: Iee57811be5434d27ea90342f2aa9439a0518d30c

commit_message:
Port remote_fs driver to use new driver model

Port glusterfs and nfs drivers to ABC classes. Abstract
San class must be ported as well, otherwise we will have
a inheritance loop for IBM NAS driver.

Change-Id: I905c0256402472de87c7fccb922c207ce5a0e483
Implements: blueprint abc-driver-update

commit_message:
Fix wrong check when use image in local

When use bdm to boot with image in local,we should check
whether boot_index is valid firstly.

For example,when use novaclient,boot_index is a string ,
it can't compare with integer directly.

Change-Id: I8c0c3793e4453b9a5d6daac7404c281c163ac474
Closes-bug:#1459917

commit_message:
Use a class constant for the default path based backend path

When no path is provided to a path based backend via configuration
use a class constant to provide the default, and override this in
backends that support providing defaults.

Change-Id: I0a6c88398403a162b113e34abe7e56821d1f02bc

commit_message:
Fixed empty yaml load

This change fixes the py_pkgs plugin so that if the plugin loads an empty file
or if there is an exception raised when loading the contents of a yaml file
the item will be skipped and no bad data will be passed onto the rest of the
plugin.

Change-Id: Ica3af42d95e7f3140e437e388b25f41bc14db47f
Closes-Bug: #1464673
(cherry picked from commit 1132f99b477211ed2b287ce6ee8718abf3434579)

The bootstrap-aio.sh script generates a password by reading a set number
of characters from urandom then removing those that aren't alphanumeric.
The problem with this is that its possible for 0 characters to remain.

This patch changes the order so that tr (translate) reads urandom
directly and removes non alphanumeric characters then that output is
truncated to the required length. This ensures the generated password is
always the desired length.

Change-Id: I03984ab891f88fe4b064f7f7fcb71edf48096493
Closes-Bug: #1465684
(cherry picked from commit b98422b9743c7536a82ad9f07f2e86ddddf831c5)
"}]
commit_message:
Generate consistent length passwords in AIO

The bootstrap-aio.sh script generates a password by reading a set number
of characters from urandom then removing those that aren't alphanumeric.
The problem with this is that its possible for 0 characters to remain.

This patch changes the order so that tr (translate) reads urandom
directly and removes non alphanumeric characters then that output is
truncated to the required length. This ensures the generated password is
always the desired length.

Change-Id: I03984ab891f88fe4b064f7f7fcb71edf48096493
Closes-Bug: #1465684
(cherry picked from commit b98422b9743c7536a82ad9f07f2e86ddddf831c5)

commit_message:
Implement service_region user_group_var

Currently each service has an individual service_region var
which needs to be set when setting up a region that is
different to the default.

This patch implements a user_group_var called 'service_region'
which can be used to set the region for all services.

The AIO bootstrap script is also altered to set the
service_region in the user config.

Change-Id: I5ed216916f667506ffed900a01744dad973221bf
Closes-Bug: #1463366
(cherry picked from commit 337f9949dfc4865ad24353ec0380de0222167a67)

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: If9e7dd93737cc13654e01f1b923cb29f434e8425

commit_message:
Remove invalid client config option

Removing the unnecessary config allows clients to run without changing the
results returned by:

> SHOW VARIABLES LIKE  'char%';

Indicating that we have not stepped out of a UTF-8 only configuration.

Closes-bug: #1463457
Change-Id: Ifad24dc9b1b6de6dee14222e29affc584723817b

[{'created': '2015-05-19 18:16:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fix Server.start() on Python 3.4

os.dup() now creates a non-inheritable file descriptor since Python 3.4
because of the PEP 446 "Make newly created file descriptors
non-inheritable":
https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0446/

Server.start() uses os.dup() to pass a socket to a child process, so the
file descriptor must be inheritable. If os.set_inheritable() is
available (Python 3.4 or newer), make the file descriptor inheritable.

Change-Id: I7e5a24453cf837391e1fad73b7bb0c0fbd8963e2
'}, {'created': '2015-05-27 01:07:30.000000000', 'message': 'Fix Server.start() on Python 3.4

os.dup() now creates a non-inheritable file descriptor since Python 3.4
because of the PEP 446 "Make newly created file descriptors
non-inheritable":
https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0446/

Server.start() uses os.dup() to pass a socket to a child process, so the
file descriptor must be inheritable.

Add pass_fds parameter to fork_exec() of glance.tests.utils: optional
sequence of file descriptors, similar to the pass_fds parameter of
subprocess.Popen. On Python 3.4 and newer, fork_exec() calls
os.set_inheritable() on these file descriptors to make thee inheritable.

Use pass_fds in Server.start().

Change-Id: I7e5a24453cf837391e1fad73b7bb0c0fbd8963e2
'}]
commit_message:
Fix Server.start() on Python 3.4

os.dup() now creates a non-inheritable file descriptor since Python 3.4
because of the PEP 446 "Make newly created file descriptors
non-inheritable":
https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0446/

Server.start() uses os.dup() to pass a socket to a child process, so the
file descriptor must be inheritable.

Add pass_fds parameter to fork_exec() of glance.tests.utils: optional
sequence of file descriptors, similar to the pass_fds parameter of
subprocess.Popen. On Python 3.4 and newer, fork_exec() calls
os.set_inheritable() on these file descriptors to make thee inheritable.

Use pass_fds in Server.start().

Change-Id: I7e5a24453cf837391e1fad73b7bb0c0fbd8963e2

subject: Add a non-voting Python 3.4 job to Glance
messages:
[{'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-06-10 13:06:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-06-10 13:22:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

IMO a py34 check job on Glance is useless right now. "tox -e py34" fails early: it tries to install MySQL-Python and qpid-python which are not Python 3 compatible. There is https://review.openstack.org/#/c/184373/ for PyMySQL, but not patch yet for qpid-python.

Even without these dependencies, testr fails to load tests, and so it's unable to run a single unit test. There is no need to waste infra resources to know which parts of Glance require more work.

Please wait until more Glance Python 3 fixes will be merged:

https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:openstack/glance+branch:master+topic:py3,n,z

Right now, only one of my Glance Python 3 was merged.

By the way, I didn't finish to port glance_store fully to Python 3:

https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:openstack/glance_store+branch:master+topic:py3,n,z

There is also a pending review to add a py34 check job for glance_store, but glance_store is in a better shape for Python 3.

commit_message:
Add a non-voting Python 3.4 job to Glance

This will help the Glance team determine when we can start gating on
Python 3.4. This should also help Victor Stinner (and others) in his
efforts to add Python 3 compatibility to Glance.

Change-Id: Icac9c01821ece45afafc329630f578502f78520f

commit_message:
Remove inappropriate 'self' params

In LBaaS driver, there were several places where 'self' object is
passed in as an argument incorrectly.  This patch removes them.

Change-Id: Ief0b66941f08e8cf01fbc7e06714eb53830c9b51
Fixes: MNP-152

There are two roots for the current exception hierarchy: VimException
and VMwareDriverException, which is not a good design. This patch
refactors the exception hierarchy to fix this problem.

VMwareDriverException is a suitable candidate for the root since the
library is consumed by VMware drivers. Therefore, the parent of
VimException is changed from Exception to VMwareDriverException.

The guidelines followed for this refactoring are:
* The changes in existing driver code should be NIL.

* The changes in other parts of the library should be minimal.

* Any exception raised by a service (vim or pbm) should be a child of
ServiceException. This would result in two child nodes:
VimException and PbmException. Any exception raised by invocation of
vim APIs should be a VimException and similarly for pbm APIs. But this
change would result in lot of changes in the library as well as existing
clients. Therefore, these three nodes are merged into a single node and
labelled as VimException instead of ServiceException.

* Any exception raised by the library should be a child of
VMwareDriverException.Therefore, VimException is a child of
VMwareDriverException.

* Any configuration related exception should be a child of
VMwareDriverConfigurationException which in turn is a child of
VMwareDriverException.

There are two roots for the current exception hierarchy: VimException
and VMwareDriverException, which is not a good design. This patch
refactors the exception hierarchy to fix this problem.

Summary of changes:
* Change parent of VimException to VMwareDriverException
* Change parent of exceptions corresponding to known VIM faults
  to VimException
* Change parent of VimSessionOverLoadException, VimConnectionException,
  VimAttributeException and ImageTransferException to
  VMwareDriverException.

The guidelines followed for this refactoring are:
* The changes in existing driver code should be NIL.

* The changes in other parts of the library should be minimal.

* Any exception raised by invocation of vim APIs should be a VimException
  and any exception raised by pbm APIs should be a PbmException. But this
  will result in lot of changes in the library as well as existing clients.
  Therefore, we  define a single root for these two types of exceptions which
  is labeled as VimException.

* Any exception raised by the library should be a child of
  VMwareDriverException. Therefore, VimException, VimSessionOverLoadException,
  VimConnectionException, VimAttributeException and ImageTransferException
  are children of VMwareDriverException. Ideally, VMwareDriverException
  should be renamed as ServiceException, but it will result in backward
  incompatibility.

Change-Id: Ide1bf891be78766e8670f8446792e3dc9c7ec88f

commit_message:
Exception hierarchy refactoring

There are two roots for the current exception hierarchy: VimException
and VMwareDriverException, which is not a good design. This patch
refactors the exception hierarchy to fix this problem.

Summary of changes:
* Change parent of VimException to VMwareDriverException
* Change parent of exceptions corresponding to known VIM faults
  to VimException
* Change parent of VimSessionOverLoadException, VimConnectionException,
  VimAttributeException and ImageTransferException to
  VMwareDriverException.

The guidelines followed for this refactoring are:
* The changes in existing driver code should be NIL.

* The changes in other parts of the library should be minimal.

* Any exception raised by invocation of vim APIs should be a VimException
  and any exception raised by pbm APIs should be a PbmException. But this
  will result in lot of changes in the library as well as existing clients.
  Therefore, we  define a single root for these two types of exceptions which
  is labeled as VimException.

* Any exception raised by the library should be a child of
  VMwareDriverException. Therefore, VimException, VimSessionOverLoadException,
  VimConnectionException, VimAttributeException and ImageTransferException
  are children of VMwareDriverException. Ideally, VMwareDriverException
  should be renamed as ServiceException, but it will result in backward
  incompatibility.

Change-Id: Ide1bf891be78766e8670f8446792e3dc9c7ec88f

commit_message:
Add ability to specify cinder lvm_type option

Cinder has had an lvm_type option for quite a while
that allows the LVM driver to be configured to use
thin provisioning.

This required an additional PPA in Precise, but is
available in the default Trusty packages.

This patch adds the lvm_type option, and we'll use
it to do gate testing against the lvm_thin configuration.

[{'created': '2015-06-20 16:11:53.000000000', 'message': 'Fix propose_update.sh

The propose-requirements-updates was failing since we essentially call
virtualenv `mktemp` - but mktemp creates a file and virtualenv expects a
directory.

Add -d to mktemp invocation to create a directory.

Change-Id: I358bd2c42d698de4d7863ac08318d46a4524e32b
'}, {'created': '2015-06-20 16:14:04.000000000', 'message': 'Fix propose_update.sh

The propose-requirements-updates was failing since we essentially call
virtualenv `mktemp` - but mktemp creates a file and virtualenv expects a
directory.

Add -d to mktemp invocation to create a directory.

Change-Id: I358bd2c42d698de4d7863ac08318d46a4524e32b
'}]
commit_message:
Fix propose_update.sh

The propose-requirements-updates was failing since we essentially call
virtualenv `mktemp` - but mktemp creates a file and virtualenv expects a
directory.

Add -d to mktemp invocation to create a directory.

Change-Id: I358bd2c42d698de4d7863ac08318d46a4524e32b

commit_message:
Override opportunistic database tests to PyMySQL

Set the OS_TEST_DBAPI_ADMIN_CONNECTION override variable so that
oslo.db opportunistic detection will know to use PyMySQL until
I12b32dc097a121bd43991bc38dd4d289b65e86c1 makes it the default
behavior.

Change-Id: I1b27cbdc0612ac63501e2f132bab1c065fe9a3ba
Co-Authored-By: Victor Sergeyev <vsergeyev@mirantis.com>

 def rand_name(name=''):

of rand_name() calls.

commit_message:
Add a rule for blocking "-" from rand_name call

data_utils.rand_name() appends randam charactors with a hypen like:

 def rand_name(name=''):
     randbits = str(random.randint(1, 0x7fffffff))
     if name:
         return name + '-' + randbits

So it is not necessary to specify a hypen in caller side.
This patch adds a hacking rule for blocking "-" at the end of argument
of rand_name() calls.

Change-Id: I9b9f25dbe5a3ef5ac5900113bcc46e0d911becc9

Clients can be implemented more cpu efficiently and in simpler way, when the _exact_ time format is in the api spec.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-05-11 16:25:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm not sure that's what this patch is saying. It's still using the same format (iso 8601) the resolution is just being made variable. I don't think the resolution is specifically outlined in the keystone api for tokens. I could be wrong on that though."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-05-11 18:32:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The Keystone token expires_at is very specifically meant to be UTC time and is narrowly controlled in format because we rely on this to ensure that both Keystone and Non-Keystone consumers of the token data can determine the validity of the token. For V2 of the Keystone Auth API ( http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-identity-v2.html#identity-auth-v2 ) we specify that the expires response is "2014-01-31T15:30:58Z" (as an example) meaning that we do not supply the microseconds.

So for a couple things: 

1) No, it is incorrect to allow *any* ISO8601 format, because you can get crazy and require to know what the formatting string is to properly parse it out.

2) Keystone *could* validate a v3 token as v2 today and get a microsecond "expires_at" but that is an edge case.

3) No pure v2 token (v2 issued token) will contain microseconds.


The only way I'd consider supporting this change is if it strictly validated for microsecond and/or non-microsecond resolution expires_at in tokens for v2.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-05-11 18:36:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Allows any valid ISO8601 timestamp in token expiry time format

* The current Tempest auth providers check for a very specific
  timestamp format for the "expires" field of token responses.
  If the Identity provider sends a response with a valid timestamp
  that does not exactly match this format, test execution is halted.
  Since the auth provider is client code, any specific functional
  checks would be better represented as a test. The client is
  primarily concerned with if the value can be parsed successfully.
  The current guidance from the API working group is that any
  valid ISO 8601 compliant timestamp should be sufficient.

  https://github.com/openstack/api-wg/blob/master/guidelines/time.rst

Change-Id: I7b8e9435b5b94a6237f300366952f6d2f6414e42

commit_message:
Don't upload cases to TestRail if no groups found

If no test groups are found in Jenkins jobs, then
skip tests cases uploading to TestRail in order to
avoid uploading of all existing (fuel-qa) cases.

Change-Id: Id7e19801d3e45f7786b9ddf1a60a4ffcf4e272dd
Closes-bug: #1467098

commit_message:
Sync requirements

Additionally, OpenStack CI infra doesn't play nice with "-e git://" style
requirements, so we follow the same pattern as other -dashboard repos by
removing Horizon as a dep, and instead list out Django etc directly.

Change-Id: Ie32ab05d70bdbbf49f60862c83952586bbca2ad5
