Fixes for Influxdb 0.9 latest stable

change 'name' to 'measurement'.
Accept 200 or 204 return on writes.
change 'timestamp' to 'time'.
add precision.

Fixes for Influxd 0.9 latest

change 'name' to 'measurement'.
change 'timestamp' to 'time'.
store value_meta as "" instead of "\"\"" when empty.

commit_message:
[upstream-training] improve the index.rst file

* remove the "Indices and tables" slide

There is no need for a "Indices and tables" slide. The slide is
confusing and should be removed.

* convert the index.rst file from a default Sphinx documentation
  index.rst file into a more useful hieroglyph index.rst file

Change-Id: I15f9b5a44fd86972d6d937f11922335fa4cc1163

commit_message:
Add upper-constraints.txt generator.

This script when run creates a constraints file with exact pins for
the transitive dependencies of a requirements file.

Change-Id: I1282f8e4010c0ec46c473495bacddf044d06c0af

commit_message:
Remove the shebang from generated setup.py's.

We don't expect users to run setup.py directly, and the world didn't
end when the x bit was removed accidentally, so this just completes
the statement.

Change-Id: Ib3934e55949ed6bc72408ddf020b4300a1fccc80

commit_message:
Remove spurious output in test suite.

This was a debugging thing, but we don't need this verbosity for the
smoke test.

Change-Id: I3a088fae7048074a5f9ef6a2ca94dbd90067f0b2

commit_message:
Also update extras in setup.cfg.

This required some care. There doesn't seem to be a sane Python3 ready
comment-preserving ini parser around, so I wrote a
minimal-for-our-case one in Parsley. Parsley is already in use in
infra in bindep, but I need to add it to global-requirements as this
is the first use in a managed project of it.

Change-Id: I48de3a2f36e945f75b534f689e3af802bbdc5be9
Depends-On: I7d7e91694c9145fac0ddab8a9de5f789d723c641
Depends-On: I16e967356d5c56f1474ee661b954b3db11a608cb

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Volume driver for HP XP storage

Volume driver for HP XP storage, along with unit tests. The driver
imports the hp_xp_horcm_fc class, which is available separately to
HP XP customers.

Implements: blueprint hpxp-storage-driver

Change-Id: Ic28c7f3fc5d61e9c2304dca60e416b5e94b990db
Signed-off-by: Kazumasa Nomura <kazumasa.nomura.rx@hitachi.com>

commit_message:
Fix broken export commands on block_device driver

When I implemented the new target driver code the
methods used for LVM were copy pasted:
 commit 9651f547147188645942466602c92cce06666483

I screwed this up because the block_device driver
doesn't use LVM at all.

This patch sets it back the way it should be and just
uses the local dev file of the whole disk.

Change-Id: Ife88d5597df27dcd668a9a361bebccbc840ca2d4
Closes-Bug: #1465819

commit_message:
Add client_socket_timeout option

Add a parameter to take advantage of the new(ish) eventlet socket timeout
behaviour.  Allows closing idle client connections after a period of
time, eg:

$ time nc localhost 9292
real    1m0.063s

Setting 'client_socket_timeout = 0' means do not timeout.

NOTE(mriedem): This patch is not 1:1 cherry-pick, I have changed the
default value of client_socket_timeout to 0, as per the policy for
changes to stable branches:
(https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/StableBranch#Appropriate_Fixes)

DocImpact
Closes-bug: 1371022
Change-Id: I9e7edcbf25ece61dc16b8cd5a8bef5ed9a14e3d6
(cherry picked from commit 19bba346ba3a52ebd5a3f83d7ed259d7e8025489)

commit_message:
Refactor machine builder + runner into single unit

There is really no need to seperate off the runner into
a unit that builds a state-machine and then provides a tiny
utility function, both of these can just be in the same class
and code so that it is easier to understand/read.

Change-Id: I18b97514e230451ef804a878a0edcea4d0b2ad20

commit_message:
Handle : as well as ; for markers.

setup.cfg uses foo:MARKER rather than foo;MARKER as requirements.txt
files do. To be able to process setup.cfg sections we need to support
':' as a marker separator.

Change-Id: I3d78b3df8ea9fad1fd7b3c634eb0fb0f7e7e9124

commit_message:
Cache the individual atom schedulers at compile time

These do not need to be re-fetched/re-examined each time.

Change-Id: Ie48100caa12575c725530911ad3d1dc9046e9d26

commit_message:
Split-off the additional retry states from the task states

Split the states that are not task states (but are retry
states) into there own additional set and then use that set
and a new function to validate the transition at other locations
in the code-base.

This makes the transitions that are valid for tasks/retries
easily viewable, more easy to read and understand, and
more correct (instead of being a mix of task + retry atom
transitions and states).

Change-Id: I9515c19daf59a21e581f51e757ece2050f348214

commit_message:
Replace dit.itervalues() with dict.values()

This change adds Python 3 compatibility to the modified code.

The itervalues() method of Python 2 dictionaries was renamed to values() on
Python 3. As discussed on the openstack-dev mailing list, itervalues() must be
replaced with values(), six.itervalues() should not be used. In OpenStack, the
overhead of creating a temporary list with dict.values() on Python 2 is
negligible.

Blueprint cinder-python3

Change-Id: Ibcf4597aeef1835f08bee2d6831205c428884c31

utils: make parse_docstring respect multi-line

Make `parse_docstring' respect multi-line param docs and fix it not matching
the **kwargs.

commit_message:
Rewrite code merging two dictionaries

Basically, replace dict(dict1.items() + dict2.items()) with
dict1.update(dict2) (and copy dict1 when needed).

This change adds Python 3 compatibility to the modified code.

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I4f73efa0434f5c7ffba2dd966035762d197b9c68

commit_message:
[Manila] Add benchmark for Manila list share servers operation

List of changes:
- Added support of 'list' operation for share servers.
- Added benchmark for listing of share servers.

Change-Id: Iea34c51eaf3cf73de52f882b09592a793a3159c1

commit_message:
[Manila] Add scenario for creation and listing of Manila share networks

List of changes:
- Added support of 'list'  operation for share networks.
- Added benchmark for creating and listing share networks.

Change-Id: Ib62f3291d685a4392e26fdf55e2edac09bb3f73c

commit_message:
Huawei manila driver support Read-Only share

- Change allow_access function: Add access_level parameter
to setting 'rw' and 'ro'.
- Add unit test.

Change-Id: I9f9202242ec89c0dad27befce8992481e298d407
Implements blueprint huawei-driver-read-only-share

To be honest, I prefer the actual thing running than a fixture-like service. I'd be ok with rabbitfixture if these were just unittests but the functional nature of these tests doesn't make the fixture library sit well with me.

I think we'd need the thing running anyway since we also have qpid and zmq, which makes me advocate for having a unique and consistent way to do this for all the drivers.

lifeless, mind if we take this discussion to a bug? Since this is a backport to stable/kilo, it won't receive changes. I'm all for improving what we have in master and then update stable/kilo again.

Thanks :)"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-06-20 02:51:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Flavio, sure a bug is fine. For clarity though -rabbitfixture *is* the real thing running.'}]

commit_message:
Don't use devstack to setup our functional env

This adds a setup script for each tox functional target to start a
rabbitmq-server, qpidd or redis daemon dedicated for the functional
testing.

This script is responsible to spawn a preconfigured daemon needed for
the functional tests.

This also changes the gate script to just install the required packages
instead of setup a devstack.

This also fixes the zmq config options loading in tests

Closes-bug: #1442612

Change-Id: I27eb2c1d3d0ca67aa361c83e41372138e03d9bdd
(cherry picked from commit 80ece65a547db332b345a0a433f17602af058b56)

commit_message:
Pull serialisation out of _sync_requirements_file.

This means we can use _sync_requirements for setup.cfg stanzas, which
have a different format to requirements.txt files.

Change-Id: Ifdb612017677fa2cf3e91de09e4b152dd11ca8ed

commit_message:
HP 3PAR driver config has unused username/password

Removed all references to hp3par_username and hp3par_password in the
code and documentation as it is currently not used.
Closes-Bug: 1463942

stub those out with 'pass'; future work we need to better
identify what's actually 'required' in the abstract base class,
and also should probably do some refactoring to make these
classes in volume/targets a bit more consumable for 3'rd party
drivers.

commit_message:
Update SolidFire to use target driver model

A while back we broke the inheritance chain of transport and backend
by moving the target drivers outside of the drivers.

This means you can instantiate and use any target (data transport)
method that your device supports without requiring a separate
driver (again, if your device can support it).  This was
particularly important for the LVM ref driver and the 5 iSCSI
options that go with it.

This patch converts the SolidFire driver to use the same model.  For
the most part it's pretty simple:
* Create an internal class for the target driver
* Instantiate the target driver that you want to use
* wrap the old transport calls that come to the driver to call
  the new target driver objects

This exposed some issues with the abc work that was being done.
There are a number of items that are marked as required but are
really only necessary for LVM based drivers.  So this also
creates a san/3'rd party iSCSI subclass as well that has the
more appropriate abc settings for such devices.

Change-Id: I02ceaac58d0e4176ccad423763ae0101cfb8446b

commit_message:
Change ensure_dir to not check directory exists first

I224be69168ede8a496a5f7d59b04b722f4de7192 added an EEXIST
check, so no need to check if the directory is already
there, just try and create it.

Change-Id: Iba51fc8263bf59326489319d0dd3f69af00a8eeb

In Python 3, dict.items() returns an iterator. Iterators cannot be added.

Blueprint: neutron-python3
Change-Id: I487178ebceae9946cb53dea1e847d7715f4577f3
"}]
commit_message:
Python3: do not use '+' on dict_items objects

In Python 3, dict.items() returns an iterator. Iterators cannot be added.

Blueprint: neutron-python3

commit_message:
Update Redis elements to version 3.0

The stock kick-start elements disable installation of
packages other than Redis packages.
Apart from being not consistent with other elements
it breaks the kick-start because it cannot install dependencies.

Install Redis 3.0 and apply some recommended tweaks to the OS.
Install the native Python client for Redis.

Partial-Implements blueprint: redis-configuration-groups
Partial-Implements blueprint: redis-cluster
Change-Id: I436fd63005a1ddee27755277ca7d4680747f400c

commit_message:
Python3: do not use im_self/im_func/func_closure

One should use __self__, __func__ and __closure__ instead, as they work
with both Python 2 and 3.

Change-Id: I2b2847cfd5b4fa70e45387ff369240227ce9e526
Blueprint: neutron-python3

Ok, looks better. 

Something I would like to consider (but can be a separate review if necessary) would be to change the get_request to accept the context. It wouldn't really need any other parameters beyond that. The driver would no longer need the context when instantiating it.

So, instead of the context being embedded in the driver instance, it would be in the specific request. More to the point, the request object could interpret the context in any way it needs to in order to produce the proper request. This takes all of the "request generation" logic and puts it into the factory, where it belongs.

commit_message:
Add request factory for pluggable IPAM

Pluggable IPAM implementation requires separation between requesting
address/subnet and it's actual allocation, which can happen on
third-party IPAM servers. Request factory stands for simplifying
building right request from input.

Added AddressRequestFactory and SubnetRequestFactory.

AddressRequestFactory creates instance of AnyAddressRequest or
SpecificAddressRequest depending on presence of ip address in input.
SubnetRequestFactory creates instance of AnySubnetRequest or
SpecificSubnetRequest depending on input.

get_subnet_request_factory and get_address_request_factory can be
redefined on driver level to use custom request factories.

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: Iedc0cfa326d60810099148f0ef8a1edac9e8aa12

commit_message:
Change status code from 500 to 400 for image update request

Invalid 'op' (operation) value provided for image update PATCH request
results in raising Internal Server Error (500). There is no helpful
information what went wrong and how to fix this particular request.
Proposed fix change the status code from 500 to 400 and return proper
message, so the user won't be confused and will be able to adjust the
request.

Change-Id: Ie20a3f350cbaa46c558b4e49b46091d1e4a74807
Closes-Bug: 1456157
(cherry picked from commit 9f9629ada550c7ddf66fd03d6604e16a5712881f)

commit_message:
Add support for RabbitMQ clustering

This adds support for the rabbitmq_hosts configuration option, which if
specified will also turn on rabbit_ha_queues.  This is needed if using
RabbitMQ in clustered mode.

Change-Id: I16001fba7198f0378c31310389b407b832ad6328

commit_message:
Python3: use dict.keys() instead of dict.iterkeys()

The "keys" method works on both Python 2 and 3, and the performance
impact should be negligible.

Change-Id: I4771797859666000921e4e38cc5de72a8c084ca0
Blueprint: neutron-python3

commit_message:
Move _add_auto_addrs_on_network_ports

Moved to ipam_non_pluggable_backend.py since implementation
is specific for non pluggable ipam backend.
Pluggable implementation will additionally include rollback on failure actions.

This commit is a preparation step for using pluggable ipam.
More changes in this methods are expected to be done by following
patches.

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: I1876846526e370a7fcfa05b9a23fd9065973f111

commit_message:
Add openstack_project_domain to assertion

Currently, a keystone IdP does not provide the domain of the project
when generating SAML assertions. Since it is possible to have two
projects with the same name but in different domains, this patch
adds an additional attribute called "openstack_project_domain"
in the assertion to identify the domain of the project.

Closes-Bug: 1442343
bp assertion-extra-attributes

Change-Id: I62ed73d87f268c73294738845421deb87088326b
(cherry picked from commit fa844bc88edb417f9513d19c749886a61d7b26ce)

[{'created': '2015-06-08 20:55:43.000000000', 'message': "Unpin beaker-rspec

The latest version of beaker tries to manage sshd_config[1] in order to
pass through environment variables. JJB also tries to manage
sshd_config by adding Match blocks to securely allow root SSH[2]. When
beaker tries to append the PermitUserEnvironment line after the Match
blocks, SSH fails to open port 22 and beaker can't SSH in to the
node[3]. This patch unpins beaker-rspec and adds set_env: false to the
nodepool nodesets so that the set_env method is never called and does
not try to mess with the sshd_config.

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L528

Change-Id: I69f7cfe293fa26a8bd43aef2af898db262872bc7

commit_message:
Unpin beaker-rspec

The latest version of beaker tries to manage sshd_config[1] in order to
pass through environment variables. JJB also tries to manage
sshd_config by adding Match blocks to securely allow root SSH[2]. When
beaker tries to append the PermitUserEnvironment line after the Match
blocks, SSH fails to open port 22 and beaker can't SSH in to the
node[3]. This patch unpins beaker-rspec and adds set_env: false to the
nodepool nodesets so that the set_env method is never called and does
not try to mess with the sshd_config.

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L528
[2] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/project-config/tree/jenkins/jobs/puppet-module-jobs.yaml#n42
[3] http://logs.openstack.org/61/185161/1/check/gate-puppet-nova-puppet-beaker-rspec-dsvm-centos7/cd81608/console.html.gz#_2015-05-22_22_05_46_933
[4] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L502

Change-Id: I69f7cfe293fa26a8bd43aef2af898db262872bc7

commit_message:
Run tempest tests from our post_test_hook.sh script

Migrate to running tempest out of our own post_test_hook.sh
script. This gives us more control over the tempest environment.

Change-Id: I5bd051620b441848890e4358c30f59ddbbdd6b7a
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

dropped support for py26 (we are no longer gating on it) we
should remove it as a requirement and remove references
to it in the code.

commit_message:
Remove ordereddict from requirements

Ordereddict was required for py26 support. Since we have
dropped support for py26 (we are no longer gating on it) we
should remove it as a requirement and remove references
to it in the code.

Change-Id: I648edbb5d0b51c003f08f5f5c4ce700128032b38
Partial-bug: 1445827
(cherry picked from commit 20ec82f18c368bbc8a89e79d2d6eee2de2c2a9ea)

commit_message:
Fix setup.cfg.

setup.cfg wasn't specifying the packages that we use (and had a no
longer needed bit of glue code). Without this, the installed
requirements are not usable as the library is missing.

Change-Id: I4a2bc2bfcccab00c248d42c45b4c6ec184ea740f

commit_message:
Extract redundant usage of save_and_reraise_exception

In some cases the exception context can be cleared,
resulting in None being attempted to be re-raised after
an exception handler is run. I think that previously
save_and_reraise_exception was used in places where we can't
get an inner exception.

Change-Id: I6ebca93239b489e889ccc40669a5112ede224c6c

commit_message:
Allows usage of reduced redundancy storage

This patch allows the use of S3's reduced redundancy storage
when using the S3 store.

It also eliminates an implicit boolean casting issue in the
glance.store.s3.Store._options_get function.

Change-Id: Idb6280f90ee762dad79fe109ccf3c141b6b55958
Closes-Bug: 1222963

commit_message:
SQLite file as default option

It has been included instructions that make sqlite file as default
option for synchronizing tables and columns.  It has been also
added the exclusion of db files from the scope of git.

Change-Id: I132014556e23aea6d30a5aa5796031a2c426f891
Closes-Bug: #1366361

commit_message:
Add option to push service image to Glance

The default behavior was previously to take the URL that was in
service_image_location, download it, and load that into Glance. There
are instances where this is not desired behavior, so adding a new
boolean service_image_push_to_glance. If false, it skips the Glance
loading portion, but still writes the relevant manila.conf values.

Change-Id: Ic388553f0a5779506c39a1d4cdc3894992b98afe

commit_message:
Fix logic error in gate-project-config-projects-yaml

Previously labels were only being checked for validity if an upstream
was given due to a premature 'continue' if no upstream is given before
checking labels.

commit_message:
refresh the devstack plugin docs, add plugin registry

The devstack plugin docs mostly referred to in tree plugins, which is
honestly something we don't want people doing. Instead restructure the
whole document to talk about external plugins as the only kinds of
plugins, and focus on a workflow to make that easy for people to work
through.

This also adds a plugin-registry page to start listing known plugins
somewhere centrally. Some sample content was added, hopefully people
will submit patches to include their plugins.

This does drop the section on hypervisor plugins. That's not currently
something that we expect a ton of people to work on, so diving into
the code for this should be fine.

Change-Id: Ifc0b831c90a1a45daa507a009d1dcffcd6e2deca

commit_message:
beaker: update repourl to use centos mirror

Until now, we were downloading packages from fedora mirror.
It seems using http://mirror.centos.org is the way to go for having more
recent & stable packages.

Change-Id: Ife7f2e79f94a42e61620b994513e2feec1ecfcc0

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-15 12:45:46.000000000', 'message': 'Add Neutron/Nova Floating IP list/search/get

Some clouds out there are still running nova-network but we want to
provide support for neutron specific features and concepts like ports,
networks, subnets, etc.

This change is part of a set that adds neutron support to existing
floating IP-related functions, hiding that behind resource-oriented
methods.
For instance, at high level, end-users can now request that a public IP
is assigned to an instance without worrying about the specific service,
procedures and protocols used to provide that feature in the target
cloud.

Change-Id: I35c3af4b8c43af9988463785cb48c0c41abe6abe

commit_message:
Add Neutron/Nova Floating IP list/search/get

Some clouds out there are still running nova-network but we want to
provide support for neutron specific features and concepts like ports,
networks, subnets, etc.

This change is part of a set that adds neutron support to existing
floating IP-related functions, hiding that behind resource-oriented
methods.
For instance, at high level, end-users can now request that a public IP
is assigned to an instance without worrying about the specific service,
procedures and protocols used to provide that feature.

Change-Id: I35c3af4b8c43af9988463785cb48c0c41abe6abe

Converted HA networking info to RST

Only the active/active material was converted because active/passive
is being depricated.  This CR includes planning notes.
We anticipate that this will be a very small section
that links to the Networking Guide for details.

commit_message:
don't run dsvm tests on doc only changes

If the change is only docs, don't run the dsvm changes. This will save
a lot of test resources, and make doc patches much easier for everyone
to land and faster to iterate on.

Change-Id: Id0f498089dddab4cbf4b76b97ef87546544fba99

commit_message:
Adding angular dashboard plugin mechanism

We have a way to dynamically inject modules at the horizon.app level, but
not a way to dynamically inject modules at the hz.dashboard level. This
patch will allow that. This way, users can pick and choose which dashboard
they want enabled without modifying source.

Change-Id: Idc772651065d0ec76b28b7214408562d4d001235

Question: can this be put into a dnsmasq.conf file and Ironic just installs it, then tweaks the dhcp_agent.ini file to use it?'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-04-10 17:40:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Brian,

I think it would work yes. But is it a common practice for other projects to have a custom dnsmasq.conf? I thought neutron was managing dnsmasq so we shouldn't actually do anything to change it. And looking at neutron code it seems that it even has some tests looking for the ipxe tag[1], that's why I was assuming it was set by default.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/1105782e3914f601b8f4be64939816b1afe8fb54/neutron/tests/unit/agent/linux/test_dhcp.py#L569"}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-04-10 18:11:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Lucas,

I think the test you mentioned is just adding a tag to a port, don't think it's actually doing anything with ipxe.

And regarding using a custom dnsmasq.conf file, I'm not sure what other projects are doing there.  But I do know that as a cloud provider we use a custom one here for our deployment, and just tweak the ini file to point at ours instead of the default one on the system (or shipped with any neutron package).

I'm not necessarily against this change, but it seems like something deployment-specific and not something that would apply to all neutron users."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-04-10 22:40:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Brian,

Thanks for the asnwer. Right, yes that test is just adding a tag to a port. But it seems to have to do iPXE: "tag:ipxe,bootfile-name,pxelinux.0" basically says that if the request comes from iPXE, dnsmasq should ACK with the pxelinux.0 binary (standard PXE). In Ironic we do the same but the other way around, if request does not come from iPXE, dnsmasq should ACK with the iPXE binary (undionly.kpxe)[1].

But for that to work the tag should be created (which is what this patch is doing). And to do that we can always create it by default like this patch or use a custom dnsmasq.conf as you suggest.

As for it's deployment-specific, you're correct it will only be used when neutron is being used in conjuction with Ironic. But since we already have PXE boot support in neutron which is also only used by Ironic (and previously nova baremetal, I believe)[2] so having this tag set by default to simplify the way Ironic is setup (not having to carry a dnsmasq.conf etc...) would be really nice. It also will not do any harm for other neutron users.

So, I leave it to the neutron community to decide. Nethertheless I dind't know about the custom dnsmasq.conf prior to this patch, so it's all good, I'm happy that we have more than one way to solve this problem nicely.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/master/ironic/common/pxe_utils.py#L261-L262
[2] https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/pxeboot-ports

Thanks'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2015-04-14 05:46:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-04-15 10:02:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Does this change have side-effects for non-Ironic deployments? Should this be a default behavior?'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-04-16 09:24:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Sean,

Thanks for the review. There's no side effects, all it does is create a tag non-Ironic deployments will just not use it.

So being the default behavior is something I would like to have an opinion from you guys. As creating a tag is harmless and facilitate Ironic life so we don't have to add extra configuration to Neutron having it by default would be good for us. But I also understand that this tag doesn't make sense for other types of deployment (currently only ironic makes use of the neutron PXE capabilities) so I can understand if you guys don't want to have it being by default."}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-04-16 19:09:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The only concern I have is if someone is if in a non-ironic deployment, someime tries to use PXE to boot guest instances and if adding this tag would interfere.

I'm not an expert on Ironic/TripleO or PXE though. Perhaps the case I just stated they'd also want this change."}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-04-16 19:10:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Is it possible that we could have this tag be added via the API, inside the extra_dhcp_opts field? Basically look for a PXE value then start the DHCP agent with this command line flag?'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-04-17 09:34:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Sean,

Yeah, the tag won't interfere if they don't use it. But I suspect that someone using iPXE/gPXE would benefit from this tag, this is a pretty common setup for dnsmasq + iPXE.

You can google it, here's some real examples:

- http://www.richud.com/wiki/Network_iPXE_dnsmasq_Examples_PXE_BOOT#dnsmasq.conf_real_DHCP_server 

- http://lordsith.net/blog/deploying-ipxe-server-in-a-smartos-zone/

You will find a variation of names for this tag, gpxe or ipxe. That's because gpxe is deprecated since 2010 and ipxe is the project being maintained now[1]

So the tag should be created before setting the extra_dhcp_opts, I don't know if you can create it there (I think you can not :-/, I'll take a better look into it)

Yeah, we could potentially make neutron look for this tag and if it's set in the dhcp extra opts it would the DHCP agent with it. It sounds a bit overcomplex, but is a possibility. 

[1] http://ipxe.org/faq#fnt__1"}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-04-17 20:55:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the information Lucas, sorry to be asking these questions in a review'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-04-20 08:41:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Sean,

No problem at all, this is the right place to ask questions. So do you want me to change the methodology here? Make Neutron create the tag if it's not there or something?"}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-04-20 16:20:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Let's take it to the ML to discuss further"}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-04-21 07:37:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

So if I understand this correctly, this is just setting a tag so that extra dhcp options can match on it later. This doesn't actually affect the default responses at all. Is that correct?

If that's the case, I don't think I see any issue with merging this in its current state."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-04-21 08:28:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Kevin,

Yes, that's correct. We set this tag so Ironic can match on it when using iPXE instead of standard PXE for network boot."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-04-21 11:49:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The change is fine.

One of my concerns is that we introduce a special meaning for a tag name without documenting it anywhere. I would be glad if the feature would be properly documented, so DocImpact (or even APIImpact?) would be appreciated.

It's also a bit complicated due to the fact that DHCP agent is officially pluggable. Even though most setups rely on dnsmasq implementation, it may not be the case for all 3 party implementations. Are we ok making DHCP agent behaviour potentially platform dependent?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 22:59:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
DHCP agent: Set an "ipxe" tag to work with Ironic

Ironic expects neutron to have an "ipxe" tag for the option 175 which is
sent by iPXE/gPXE when booting a node. The problem is that up to now this
tag was not created by Neutron, causing the nodes deployed with Ironic
+ iPXE to fail to boot. This patch is creating this tag when launching
the dnsmasq process.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I45a0f51365b37e7d85848fcdcbcf7aa6a1dddfed
Closes-Bug: #1442123

[{'created': '2015-06-18 16:02:06.000000000', 'message': 'fields: report what the wrong type was when coerce fails

The coerce method impls all raise an exception when the
python type provided for a field does not match what was
required. Sometimes it is pretty hard to figure out what
the wrong type was, so report this along with the desired
type

This changes the exception message from something like

 "A datetime.datetime is required in field start"

to

 "A datetime.datetime is required in field start, not a str"

which can help debugging.

Change-Id: I53535e7af2165285ef1804f03f0beebe8fc42a59
'}]
commit_message:
fields: report what the wrong type was when coerce fails

The coerce method impls all raise an exception when the
python type provided for a field does not match what was
required. Sometimes it is pretty hard to figure out what
the wrong type was, so report this along with the desired
type

This changes the exception message from something like

 "A datetime.datetime is required in field start"

to

 "A datetime.datetime is required in field start, not a str"

which can help debugging.

Change-Id: I53535e7af2165285ef1804f03f0beebe8fc42a59

commit_message:
Remove block device from the management partition

Parallel to discover_vscsi_disk, the new method
nova_powervm.virt.powervm.mgmt.remove_block_dev provides the ability to
remove a block device and its associated special files from the
management partition.

Change-Id: I736cc8298d74ce657928dcaf2ccdd8c60495dc18

commit_message:
Fix unit tests from initial import

Two problems are preventing glance's unit tests passing -
  * 'members' was conditional on image visibility; for consistency
    I've changed serialization so 'members' is always present even
    if empty
  * is_public isn't a field glanceclient.v2 returns and was inconsistent
    in the one place it was specified in the test file

Also adds initial .pot file which is required by pep8 tests.

Change-Id: I6bddae7f2891f6089bf821fb8b14686020745a51

commit_message:
Fixed the only sphinx warning in docs

We made previous attempt to get rid of all warnings, but it turned out
that gate does not execute tox's docs job but runs build_sphinx
directly.

The latter behaviour should be fixed, but while at it, we
should prepare neutron job to be executed in gate by cleaning up all
warnings.

Closes-Bug: #1466554

[{'created': '2015-06-08 13:48:07.000000000', 'message': 'Decompose db_base_plugin_v2.py with changes

1. Moved get_subnets functionality to db_base_plugin_common to make it
accessible by ipam backends.
2. Reworked update_subnet routine:
- moved db part into update_db_subnet;
- passing current allocation_pools to update_db_subnet to allow
  appropriate rollback actions to be done by pluggable ipam backend
  in case of update failure;
- tracking changed fields in dict;
- moved rebuild_availabitily_ranges call to top level
  from _update_subnet_allocation_pools to make overridable
  by backends.
3. Reworked update_port routine:
- moved validations into _validate_port_for_update;
- updating ip addresses for port is backend specific
  and moved into _update_port_with_ips;
- writing port changes to db is moved into _update_db_port;
4. Updated _update_ips_for_port:
- removed unused port_id from argument list;
- updated to return added, original and removed ips;

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: Idb8f54d9fccaad1137222d156590c37d86aa576b

commit_message:
Decompose db_base_plugin_v2.py with changes

This commit is a preparation step for using pluggable IPAM.
1. Moved get_subnets functionality to db_base_plugin_common to make it
accessible by ipam backends.
2. Reworked update_subnet routine:
- moved db part into update_db_subnet;

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: Idb8f54d9fccaad1137222d156590c37d86aa576b

commit_message:
Add a script to safely update feature branches

This automates the process that used to be described on the wiki for
updating feature branches:

  https://wiki.openstack.org/w/index.php?title=Obsolete:GerritJenkinsGit&oldid=73783#Merge_Commits

This content appears to have been removed from the wiki and lost in the
transition to <http://docs.openstack.org/>.

In addition to the process outlined on the old wiki page, this includes
some extra automation to ensure consistent results -- and to ensure that
gerrit is not flooded with hundreds of new reviews at once by mistake.

Change-Id: I24976e99fa21bd1d724e0619b4927098b702c840

If the model change (though it's not expected to), you just have to improve Ceilometer by feeding the new fields to Gnocchi. They shouldn't be any change in the type of attributes in Gnocchi, or that'd be an API breakage AFAICT.

Not sure about where to put models? The Gnocchi dispatcher is part of Ceilometer so…?

We don't really care about volume=1 sample in Gnocchi, it's easy to store, so we can afford keeping them, and they can be seen as heartbeat.


Gnocchi tracks the state of resources indeed, and it consolidates them with history etc… It's a usage of event indeed, it does not replace them, thought it might be way easier for people wanting to have this date to use Gnocchi than to build their own history of resources using events.

Though Gnocchi does not cover things like tracking a serie of events to see "what happened".'}, {'account_id': 6924, 'date': '2015-06-15 16:06:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Patch Set 5 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-15 17:33:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

I'm inclinded to think that as long as the code is enforcing the policy and you can configure the policy to do this, then the code should allow it.

I get confused with the @require_admin_context stuff that was removed from the DB API so that someone using v2.1 and configure their policy to say, let non-admins list hosts, it works - but in v2 API as part of that work we keep an admin requirement in the code for backwards compatibility - even though that was arguably broken in v2 API."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-06-17 18:52:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I don't think it needs a microversion as its arguably a really weird bug (ignoring a parameter for no good reason).

However the fact that without a policy change people just got openned up to the wide world of information exposure, we definitely need to warn people that it's really important to update their policy after this change."}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-06-17 20:16:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

shouldn't the default policy be that even admins can't do this? They're admins for this tenant. That doesn't make them admins for other tenants..."}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2015-06-18 11:26:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

We have another case https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179569/ and we agreement on it need microversions...

When this parameter enable for some users, then the client code can't distinguish the current Openstack whether support this parameter.(Old deployment just ignore, new deployment can return expected result.)
So this sounds like need a microversion.

@Sean, does this make sense?"}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-06-18 20:29:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Alex, I think we didn't change the 
--all-tenants param, only change the behavior to this param,right? User should not be aware the bug when they use it?"}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-06-18 21:45:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I don't believe this needs a microversion, because I'm not really sure what it would indicate to a client.  The parameter is accepted in all cases, but only does a thing if you have the right policy.  None of that changes.  What's changing is the ability of the policy to allow non-admin users."}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-06-18 21:52:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

this is clearly a bug that needs to be fixed for both v2 and v2.1 so we don't need a spec as we don't need a microversion (and we don't have microversions in v2)."}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-06-18 21:52:53.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-06-19 19:16:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

For the record, I agree with alaski.'}]

[{'created': '2015-06-12 16:49:26.000000000', 'message': 'Allow list all instances for non-admin based on policy

commit_message:
Use environment requirement markers

Certain requirements do not need to exist on py3.x or py2.7
where they have been built-in and/or included into the
standard library so denote these requirements using the
new requirement markers capability of pbr (and python).

commit_message:
Allow FixedIntervalLoopingCall continue after exceptions in callee

In some cases we don't want Looping call to iterrupt if there is
an uncaught exception in the callee. In case of exception LoopingCall
needs to wait similarly as if a call succeeded.

Change-Id: Ifbebcf53f4c20ab0339fbe6797518810f59bee38

commit_message:
Take configuraiton control to test hooks for networking-odl

This will enable us to reduce the dependency on Tempest, just
as much as the other Neutron/-* jobs do, and long term allow
us to drive testing efforts directly from networking-odl

commit_message:
The malformed sentences under domain names are corrected.

Remove the words "user controlled content" in the first
paragraph.

Replace the words "and advise against" with "rather than".

Closes-Bug: #1447302
Change-Id: I81b5238db21ebc3dbcc8e24107163daa9e18efd1

commit_message:
Add show_legacy_releases.sh

Print a list of the tags that look like legacy releases so we can pick

commit_message:
Recommend users of service.py use `launch_service_class`

Instead of having a complete/fulfilled service object be
what is launched, instead recommend that a service class
is passed in that will become a 'actual' service after fork.

This will avoid the issues with the complete/fulfilled
service object opening sockets, or performing other actions
in its constructor (which causes later issues with sockets
and open file descriptors) by delaying that constructor call
until after forking.

Change-Id: I54feece31d40e8e03661633cf5ec3080cd9999e2

commit_message:
[stable/juno] Nail Manila branch and Manilaclient tag in Devstack

stable/juno branch of Manila is not compatible with latest Manilaclient,
so set compatible tag "1.0.1" for Manilaclient in Devstack and "stable/juno"
branch for Manila itself, which will be useful for local deployments by users.

Change-Id: I3e2092e3fa37d52d1b96de501efc711ab8a24827

commit_message:
Add cinder into the docker compose setup

This patch adds the docker-compose files, updates the docs,
and adds cinder to the start command.

Implements: blueprint container-set-storage-operation

Change-Id: I5386851e2247c00696704dc26a8a286451d4bf59

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-27 14:40:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add encryption-type-update to cinderclient

This modification adds support for updating volume encryption types.
The encryption-type-update command requires a single argument, the
name or ID of the volume type whose associated encryption type should
be updated, and up to four optional arguments representing new values
for the encryption type attributes. The update implementation supports
three use cases:

1. The user wants to specify new values for attributes of an
   encryption type.
   - include the attribute and its new value at invocation
2. The user wants to preserve the values for attributes of an
   encryption type.
   - exclude the attribute at invocation
3. The user wants to set the values for attributes of an encryption
   type to provider defaults.
   - include the attribute but provide no value at invocation

The encryption type may only be updated if the associated volume type
is unused.

NOTE: This modification is dependent upon the integration of encryption
      type update support into cinder. Until this occurs, this patch
      will be marked as "Work In Progress." See the following patch for
      more information:
      https://review.openstack.org/#/c/58344/

blueprint: encrypt-cinder-volumes
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/encrypt-cinder-volumes

Change-Id: I8e6a37428e76ba69a422468630fdb66b4fe460ab

commit_message:
Add encryption-type-update to cinderclient

This modification adds support for updating volume encryption types. The
encryption-type-update command requires a single argument, the name or
ID of the volume type whose associated encryption type should be
updated, and up to four optional arguments representing new values for
the encryption type attributes. The update implementation supports three
use cases:

1. The user wants to specify new values for attributes of an
   encryption type.
   - include the attribute and its new value at invocation
2. The user wants to preserve the values for attributes of an
   encryption type.
   - exclude the attribute at invocation
3. The user wants to set the values for attributes of an encryption
   type to provider defaults (only valid for cipher and key-size).
   - include the attribute but provide no value at invocation

The encryption type may only be updated if the associated volume type is
unused.

This modification leverages update support for encryption types provided
by the cinder volume encryption type API extension. See the following
patch for more information:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/58344/

blueprint: encrypt-cinder-volumes
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/encrypt-cinder-volumes

Change-Id: I8e6a37428e76ba69a422468630fdb66b4fe460ab
DocImpact

commit_message:
Update version for Liberty

Update the version for Liberty, switching from date-based versioning
to pre-versioning using SemVer. See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/065211.html
and
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067082.html
for details.

Change-Id: I6a35fa0dda798fad93b804d00a46af80f08d475c

commit_message:
Store context in local store after spawn_n

After a utils.spawn_n call we lose the context for logging because it's
not in the local thread store.  This was causing log lines to miss
context.  Additionally a call to context.get_admin_context() would add
that context to the local store making it appear that the context had
changed during a request.

This wraps methods being called with spawn_n so that they add the
context to the local store immediately.

Closes-Bug: 1404268

Change-Id: Ia5175c9729069df3d779237ba6039cf5bc920018

commit_message:
Create an OSC plugin for heat-translator

Creating the framework for an OSC plugin for heat-translator.
This will make adding new commands easier, incorporates them into
OSC, and provides the capabilities of authentication should
it be required in the future (using heatclient after translating
a template).

partially implements bp openstack-client-heat-translator

Change-Id: Ie477eac9acd9ed26f00069947af0d25b3c7e67b1

'}, {'created': '2015-06-16 20:46:17.000000000', 'message': "Fix functional test gate and network resource

I think a change in the gate has triggered a different behavior
and now we can not create a server without a network.

When I went to find an available internal network, I realized
there was a difference in the network resource.  The documentation
indicates the attribute is resource:external, but my devstack and
the gate are using resource_type = 'Internal' or 'External'.  I've
added a method that should handle both cases.

Closes-Bug: #1465813

commit_message:
Fix functional test gate

I think a change in the gate has triggered a different behavior
and now we can not create a server without a network.

Also, I've added a wait for delete method to wait for the vms to
be deleted so the network delete works properly.

Change-Id: I2ec28f62de10147ab8d65e0ad15d94854f6e3aeb

commit_message:
Use host_device mode for qemu-img

When writing to a host device, possibly one that does not support holes,
it is preferable to use host_device instead of the raw mode. Not doing so
means holes are simply skipped and the deployed image is invalid.

Change-Id: I24f8b4daf099af8bb03c3a4f6417b6c87bd49021
Closes-Bug: #1466632

commit_message:
Support variations of external network attribute

When I went to find an available internal network, I realized
there was a difference in the network resource.  The documentation
indicates the attribute is resource:external, but my devstack and
the gate are using resource_type = 'Internal' or 'External'.  I've
added a method that should handle both cases.

Change-Id: I72c889a2314ddafda1a4134a51b85aa05e198a7d
Closes-Bug: #1465813
